{"term":"1962","caseName":"Moseley v. Electronic & Missile Facilities, Inc.","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1962/401","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 16, 1963","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren11/oral_argument_audio/14078","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 401, United States for the use of H.W. Moseley and Moseley Plumbing and Heating Company, petitioners, versus Electronic and Missile Facilities, Incorporated.","start":0,"stop":15.082,"duration":15.08},{"text":"Mr. Grant.","start":15.082,"stop":18.115,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":18.115,"stop":21.987,"duration":3.87},{"text":"This Court granted certiorari to review a decision of the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals which had reversed a decision of the District Court for the Middle District of Georgia.","start":21.987,"stop":34.299,"duration":12.31},{"text":"The suit was brought by Moseley or United States for the use of Moseley against Electronic and Missile Facilities, a defendant who had performed a contract at one of Robins Air Force Base and Turner Air Force Base in Georgia for the construction of Nike Hercules facilities, anti-missile missile, as I understand the construction was to afford the site for the launching of that type of missile.","start":34.299,"stop":65.826,"duration":31.53},{"text":"Suit was brought by Moseley to -- who was a subcontractor of the prime contractor to recover balances due to him and unpaid for his construction work. Moseley had entered into a subcontract with the prime contractor.","start":65.826,"stop":84.926,"duration":19.1},{"text":"We point out in the brief that the subcontract was 13 pages of fine print.","start":84.926,"stop":93.205,"duration":8.28},{"text":"In the record it takes about 40 pages or so to print that.","start":93.205,"stop":97.446,"duration":4.24},{"text":"It's a printed form except for pa -- a piece of one page which described the work to be done and some slight changes on another page and writing in their mouths, otherwise it's a printed, small print form.","start":97.446,"stop":114.03,"duration":16.58}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":114.03,"stop":118.406,"duration":4.38}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"This is a photo stat of the contract if Your Honor please.","start":118.406,"stop":122.897,"duration":4.49}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":122.897,"stop":125.544,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll be glad to test to the collect, if I may.","start":125.544,"stop":133.6,"duration":8.06},{"text":"At the time the suit was brought in the middle -- in the District Court in Macon, Georgia, it was alleged that the defendant prime contractor had begun purported arbitration proceedings in the City of New York in connection with the balance due to Mr. Moseley.","start":133.6,"stop":153.427,"duration":19.83},{"text":"Our petition was brought in -- our complaint brought in six counts, two of them seeking to recover directly on the contract, the next -- and the two contracts, one at Robins, one at Turner Air Force Base.","start":153.427,"stop":166.19,"duration":12.76},{"text":"The next two counts seeking to rescind those contracts because of fraud of the prime contractor as detailed in the complaint, and seeking thereunder to recover on quantum meruit for the value of the work done, and the other two counts with respect to the two contracts saying, “Even if we're not entitled to recover on the letter of the contract, even if we can't show enough fraud to rescind it and recover in quantum meruit, we are nevertheless entitled to recover the value of the work that was done, less was been paid and any damage sustained by defendant.”","start":166.19,"stop":199.741,"duration":33.55},{"text":"It was alleged that the complainant could not possibly present his case before an Arbitration Board in the City of New York, some six or seven hundred miles from Macon, Georgia where the plaintiff lived, where his witnesses resided, where the Government records were available by which he could prove his case, and that he just simply could not properly present his case before an arbitration panel even if it could be properly presented if the evidence were there.","start":199.741,"stop":230.882,"duration":31.14},{"text":"The trial judge found that enforcement of a contract provision purporting to provide that any claim or dispute be settled by arbitration was contrary to the public policy of Miller Act, and refused to grant the motion of the defendant for a stay of the District Court suit while arbitration was undertaken in New York, and continued to enforce an injunction against him, proceeding with the arbitration in New York.","start":230.882,"stop":263.679,"duration":32.8},{"text":"Upon appeal by the defendant to the Fifth Circuit, the District Court was reversed in a two to one decision, two judges holding that the stay for arbitration should have been granted and Judge Reeves dissenting, agreeing with the trial judge that enforcement of an arbitration provision was in violation of the public policy of the Miller Act.","start":263.679,"stop":289.281,"duration":25.6},{"text":"With that factual background --","start":289.281,"stop":291.055,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":291.055,"stop":291.396,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":291.396,"stop":291.582,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There's no plain here that this arbitration [Inaudible] were obtained [Inaudible]","start":291.582,"stop":301.052,"duration":9.47}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Not insofar as not permitting him to read it, if Your Honor please, but there is an allegation that the prime contractor conceived a scheme to defraud this subcontractor as well as all other subcontractors.","start":301.052,"stop":317.226,"duration":16.17},{"text":"That he entered into the prime -- the subcontract with the intention at that time of not performing the one obligation which he had --","start":317.226,"stop":325.883,"duration":8.66}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There's never been any decision [Inaudible]","start":325.883,"stop":328.516,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":328.516,"stop":329.718,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The whole case is turned, is it not?","start":329.718,"stop":331.092,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"The case has proceeded on the pleadings up this point.","start":331.092,"stop":334.326,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I see.","start":334.326,"stop":335.542,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"There has been no trial --","start":335.542,"stop":336.612,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] Court that was found that was not enforced [Inaudible] contrary to the policy of the Miller Act.","start":336.612,"stop":341.177,"duration":4.56}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":341.177,"stop":341.749,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The Court of Appeals [Inaudible] disagreed with the District Court.","start":341.749,"stop":345.623,"duration":3.87}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, Your Honor.","start":345.623,"stop":346.744,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court of Appeals would reverse, there still had to be a trial, is that it?","start":346.744,"stop":350.72,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":350.72,"stop":350.852,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well suppose it's sustained, they were still at the trial, the allegations [Inaudible]","start":350.852,"stop":354.657,"duration":3.81}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well if -- if the Circuit Court of Appeals were being sustained, we would then have to go instead of trying it in the District Court in Macon, Georgia, we'd have to go to New York to arbitrate the issue before an arbitration panel in the Supreme Court of New York.","start":354.657,"stop":369.14,"duration":14.48}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] allegation of overreaching on the part of the prime contractor of all the subcontractors in your findings.","start":369.14,"stop":380.448,"duration":11.31},{"text":"That has never been decided.","start":380.448,"stop":381.65,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that has not been decided.","start":381.65,"stop":382.971,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well if the Court of Appeals sustained [Inaudible] will not that issue have to be tried out in the District Court?","start":382.971,"stop":389.373,"duration":6.4}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Not under the Court of Appeals decisions, if Your Honor please because the Court of Appeals decision says that we don't allege that the specific provision as to arbitration was inserted in it by fraud that that was obtained by fraud and that even you think it's true the allegation that the whole contract was a fraudulent scheme, that still the arbitration provision would be enforced.","start":389.373,"stop":413.935,"duration":24.56},{"text":"It is what the majority opinion says.","start":413.935,"stop":416.592,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":416.592,"stop":421.589,"duration":5}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, but I take it what it means is that we'd have to try that fraud question not before the District Court but up here before an arbitration panel to decide whether or not the whole contract was entered into by fraud.","start":421.589,"stop":434.499,"duration":12.91},{"text":"And --","start":434.499,"stop":434.628,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"In New York?","start":434.628,"stop":435.77,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir and if they were entered into by fraud, it's my contention there is no contract, there is no arbitration provision because if the contract is void because of fraud then every provision in it including that for arbitration is void.","start":435.77,"stop":449.01,"duration":13.24},{"text":"And we shouldn't be up in New York deciding fraud question as to whether or not there is a contract because the only way we can get to New York if is -- there is a valid contract which contains a valid and forceful arbitration provision.","start":449.01,"stop":461.045,"duration":12.04}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":461.045,"stop":470.438,"duration":9.39}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't understand the question, Your Honor.","start":470.438,"stop":471.853,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't it your point in question [Inaudible]","start":471.853,"stop":481.247,"duration":9.39}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"My pro -- my primary point is that arbitration at all is contrary to terms of Miller Act.","start":481.247,"stop":487.158,"duration":5.91}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And geography hasn't anything to do with it?","start":487.158,"stop":489.983,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the geography accentuates the extent to which our substantive rights would be destroyed by arbitrating rather the findings of the Court.","start":489.983,"stop":496.346,"duration":6.36}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well but you'd be making the same argument that this call for arbitration in Macon, wouldn't you?","start":496.346,"stop":500.935,"duration":4.59}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it just wouldn't be as clear the extent to which our rights would be taken away by arbitration.","start":500.935,"stop":508.679,"duration":7.74},{"text":"If we could do it in Macon, well the witness -- well we wouldn't have the additional burden of not being able to get the evidence to the Arbitration Board.","start":508.679,"stop":515.807,"duration":7.13}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you be making the same argument if it were clear that you would voluntarily at arms length agreed to this arbitration provision and then changed your mind later?","start":515.807,"stop":526.084,"duration":10.28}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"I would make the same argument, Your Honor, because I take the position that the insertion of that provision is exactly contrary to the spirit of the Miller Act.","start":526.084,"stop":537.039,"duration":10.96},{"text":"And I was going to proceed to that in a moment, to point out that my client did sign the contract and it does say that among all its other provisions which I have passed up there.","start":537.039,"stop":547.309,"duration":10.27}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I assume you are not inadvertently waving an argument to the effect that you are going to -- if you are forced to have an arbitration, you would rather have it in Georgia and if the -- if the statute was revered to arbitration, so provide you're not waving your right to have it tried in Georgia rather in New York, are you?","start":547.309,"stop":571.907,"duration":24.6}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"I am not waving that.","start":571.907,"stop":573.79,"duration":1.88},{"text":"I don't think that applies, if Your Honor please.","start":573.79,"stop":575.715,"duration":1.93},{"text":"This contract provides not to be done --","start":575.715,"stop":578.238,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] several, but there are certain provisions in the Arbitration Act about where the arbitration shall be heard.","start":578.238,"stop":586.412,"duration":8.17}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there's -- in this case no proceeding to compel arbitration but there's a pro -- a motion under Section 3 of the Arbitration Act to stay the suit while arbitration you carry --","start":586.412,"stop":596.639,"duration":10.23}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"While you go to New York?","start":596.639,"stop":597.934,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":597.934,"stop":599.288,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's what you would have to do if you obey the Court's order here, go to New York to arbitrate a claim that arose in Georgia while all other witnesses are in Georgia?","start":599.288,"stop":609.359,"duration":10.07}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":609.359,"stop":610.647,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But it's one thing to say I suppose that you don't have to go to New York to arbitrate, and then another thing you say, you don't have to arbitrate at all, and if the policies of the Miller Act are against arbitration just --","start":610.647,"stop":623.856,"duration":13.21}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":623.856,"stop":625.475,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That as I say is one thing but if the policy of the Miller Act only is a venue protection only, that's all, there's the location of the proceeding then you would still have to arbitrate, you might have to do it in Georgia?","start":625.475,"stop":643.61,"duration":18.13}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well it's conceivable that that might be the result.","start":643.61,"stop":645.817,"duration":2.21},{"text":"I don't see how under the -- under the Arbitration Act if it apply, it provides that you stay the suit while you arbitrate them in accordance with the provisions of the contract as I understand.","start":645.817,"stop":654.998,"duration":9.18}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Your primary argument is that the Miller Act bars your -- them from forcing you to -- you're agreeing to arbitrate this claim anyway?","start":654.998,"stop":666.229,"duration":11.23}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":666.229,"stop":666.443,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's your primary argument.","start":666.443,"stop":666.835,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's my primary argument.","start":666.835,"stop":668.121,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I presume your basic argument is the only that you do not want to arbitrate there, you think the Miller Act prevention, you do not want to arbitrate anyway where the Act doesn't require -- the Arbitration Act doesn't require it.","start":668.121,"stop":681.693,"duration":13.57},{"text":"I asked you that because according to some of the courts who have passed on this matter, you cannot be compelled to go outside your state to arbitrate a claim of this [Inaudible]","start":681.693,"stop":692.845,"duration":11.15}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we certainly take both positions, Your Honor.","start":692.845,"stop":695.336,"duration":2.49},{"text":"That we should not be compelled to arbitrate but on top of that, we shouldn't be compelled to leave State of Georgia.","start":695.336,"stop":702.06,"duration":6.72},{"text":"I was about to mention the --","start":702.06,"stop":703.811,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":703.811,"stop":706.88,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":706.88,"stop":707.433,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":707.433,"stop":713.374,"duration":5.94}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":713.374,"stop":714.231,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":714.231,"stop":722.037,"duration":7.81}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":722.037,"stop":723.595,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":723.595,"stop":729.28,"duration":5.68}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well the only ones dealt with in this record are two in Georgia.","start":729.28,"stop":733.148,"duration":3.87},{"text":"One at, one at Robins Air Base, in fact their two sites, one on each side of the Air Base about 15 to 20 miles on each side, and two sites about 15 to 20 miles on each side of the Air Base at Albany, Georgia.","start":733.148,"stop":744.887,"duration":11.74}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":744.887,"stop":751.193,"duration":6.31}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":751.193,"stop":752.476,"duration":1.28},{"text":"We have --","start":752.476,"stop":753.351,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":753.351,"stop":764.232,"duration":10.88}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe that the record does show that, Your Honor., that some did. Certainly, I would think a majority to keep in Georgia but some -- the record show it some keep them off the states.","start":764.232,"stop":772.627,"duration":8.39}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":772.627,"stop":775.411,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":775.411,"stop":775.913,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":775.913,"stop":776.6,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":776.6,"stop":777.362,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":777.362,"stop":795.758,"duration":18.4}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":795.758,"stop":796.253,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":796.253,"stop":798.691,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"The facts as we expect to development them, Your Honor asked me outside the record is that they were awarded the contract on a low bid.","start":798.691,"stop":806.209,"duration":7.52},{"text":"That then they sent what I will call a “pressure team” into Georgia to view people down, work them down into the lowest amount they could get a heating contract or plumbing contract to itself.","start":806.209,"stop":819.381,"duration":13.17},{"text":"Get the lowest price they can get from any one man and sign up with him that there had no bids prior to entering their own bid for the prime contract.","start":819.381,"stop":827.381,"duration":8},{"text":"But that they first entered a bid, were awarded the contract and then undertook -- get the lowest price they could as to each of the separate items.","start":827.381,"stop":834.641,"duration":7.26}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":834.641,"stop":839.567,"duration":4.93}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would have thought the customary procedure, Your Honor is to obtain bids from subcontract is on the basis of which to form your own bid in arriving at a price for which you do the work from the Government and then if you get the contract your serve has a contract also and knows it to begin with it.","start":839.567,"stop":855.508,"duration":15.94},{"text":"This would -- the shop observes at beginning the contract as my understanding by the way.","start":855.508,"stop":860.567,"duration":5.06}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":860.567,"stop":865.438,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"In Macon, Georgia by reserve and then sent to New York, and they send it back sometime later as I understand it after renegotiating it.","start":865.438,"stop":875.986,"duration":10.55},{"text":"I believe those facts are not in the record and I'm talking entirely from my recollection, if I'm wrong I would apologize.","start":875.986,"stop":881.96,"duration":5.97}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":881.96,"stop":898.708,"duration":16.75}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"That is -- that is my understanding, all I think there was some transmission back and forth that he signed it in -- when one of them came back and the -- maybe get him to reduce it's price on them, I'm not sure of that though.","start":898.708,"stop":913.014,"duration":14.31},{"text":"But I was about to say that this -- the Miller Act was adopted in 1935 as the successor of the Heard Act which was repealed by the adoption of the Miller Act.","start":913.014,"stop":924.472,"duration":11.46},{"text":"The Heard Act had required just one bond for the benefit of the Government to ensure performance of the contract and for the benefit of laborers and materialmen.","start":924.472,"stop":934.84,"duration":10.37},{"text":"And experience under that Act had developed that the laborers and materialmen had to wait a long time in many cases before being paid.","start":934.84,"stop":945.407,"duration":10.57},{"text":"And if they had to settle meritorious claims for less than was due them because they needed the money and that's pointed it out by one decision of this Court which I cite in the brief.","start":945.407,"stop":957.566,"duration":12.16},{"text":"And so the Miller Act came along and provided two bonds, one for the benefit of the Government itself to ensure that the contract would be performed, another bond for the benefit of laborers and materialmen to ensure that they would be paid, that there would a solvent surety in the event the contractor did not.","start":957.566,"stop":976.936,"duration":19.37},{"text":"And this Court has had occasion to point out that the purpose of the Miller Act was to facilitate the collection of money and then facilitate suit by the unpaid laborers and materialmen.","start":976.936,"stop":991.667,"duration":14.73},{"text":"In the case of McAvoy versus United States this Court pointed out, the Miller Act while they repeal the Heard Act, reinstated these basic provisions and was designed primarily to eliminate certain procedural limitations on its beneficiaries.","start":991.667,"stop":1006.926,"duration":15.26},{"text":"There was no express purpose in the legislative history to restrict in anyway the courage of the Heard Act.","start":1006.926,"stop":1012.323,"duration":5.4},{"text":"The intent rather was to remove the procedural difficulties found to exist under the earlier measure and thereby make it easier for unpaid creditors to realize the benefit of the bonds.","start":1012.323,"stop":1025.782,"duration":13.46},{"text":"And this Court goes further to point out that under the Heard Act serious inconveniences and delays resulted to this claimant.","start":1025.782,"stop":1033.351,"duration":7.57},{"text":"They claimants often in need of immediate funds were compelled to settle meritorious claims for less than the full amount, that's quoting from this decision of this Court.","start":1033.351,"stop":1042.519,"duration":9.17},{"text":"The Miller Act was designed to meet these difficulties.","start":1042.519,"stop":1046.404,"duration":3.88},{"text":"So what did they do to meet it?","start":1046.404,"stop":1048.333,"duration":1.93},{"text":"There are two things to guard against in entering into a contract involving performance by another party.","start":1048.333,"stop":1054.518,"duration":6.18},{"text":"The first thing is the financial responsibility of the person you're contracting with.","start":1054.518,"stop":1059.214,"duration":4.7},{"text":"He may be unable financially to carry out his obligations.","start":1059.214,"stop":1062.609,"duration":3.39},{"text":"To avoid that Congress provided that this contract that must give a bond by a solvent surety.","start":1062.609,"stop":1069.15,"duration":6.54},{"text":"The other thing you have to worry about in dealing with somebody else is going to do certain performance is his innate honesty or his willingness to carry out the provisions of the contract that he enters into.","start":1069.15,"stop":1083.148,"duration":14},{"text":"And to guard against that the Miller Act inserted a provision and that is the provision giving the right to unpaid laborers and materialmen to sue but they didn't stop with the provisions that they shall have the right to sue.","start":1083.148,"stop":1102.123,"duration":18.98},{"text":"Congress went further and a put provisions in there that I don't know if any other act passed that a person unpaid who has furnished labor and material shall have the right to sue and to prosecute said action to final execution and judgment.","start":1102.123,"stop":1118.291,"duration":16.17},{"text":"Those words were deliberately inserted by Congress, we say, to give efficacy to the right to sue which they'd otherwise provided.","start":1118.291,"stop":1128.243,"duration":9.95},{"text":"We're dealing here with a subcontractor, a man who's furnishing the plumbing and heating work, a man who's a local plumber, who enters into a contract with these people to furnish the plumbing and heating work, but it should be more borne in mind in dealing with this Act that it applies not only to subcontractors that we are talking about here, but it applies to the lowliest laborer, a man who may be working for a dollar and a quarter an hour, doing some of the plumbing or who may be sweeping the floor for this general contractor, it applies just as well to him.","start":1128.243,"stop":1163.357,"duration":35.11}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Just precisely what did you say the man that contracted to do?","start":1163.357,"stop":1168.777,"duration":5.42}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"What --","start":1168.777,"stop":1169.384,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What did you say your client had contracted to do?","start":1169.384,"stop":1171.996,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"To do the plumbing and heating --","start":1171.996,"stop":1174.119,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- at what --","start":1174.119,"stop":1175.501,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"At these two facilities, one, one at Robins Airbase and another one at China Airbase.","start":1175.501,"stop":1181.403,"duration":5.9},{"text":"The construction of really housing and buildings for the --","start":1181.403,"stop":1184.797,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Construction of a housing plant in Georgia?","start":1184.797,"stop":1187.818,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it's really to house equipment, more than anything else.","start":1187.818,"stop":1190.233,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Housing equipment in Georgia?","start":1190.233,"stop":1191.831,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1191.831,"stop":1192.737,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That was your contract?","start":1192.737,"stop":1194.294,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1194.294,"stop":1195.281,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there any part of it carried on in the interstate commerce?","start":1195.281,"stop":1200.394,"duration":5.11}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Not except to the extent that materials may have been received from -- shipped from out of state there.","start":1200.394,"stop":1206.372,"duration":5.98}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well the statute, you have raised a question also about whether or not this was in commerce within the meaning of the Arbitration Act.","start":1206.372,"stop":1212.962,"duration":6.59}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1212.962,"stop":1214.292,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- was that decided against you?","start":1214.292,"stop":1217.661,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"It was decided in both places on -- in the trial court.","start":1217.661,"stop":1222.713,"duration":5.05},{"text":"That court said is not necessary to decide it --","start":1222.713,"stop":1225.184,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Not necessary --","start":1225.184,"stop":1225.551,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"That it doesn't matter, that the Miller Act just make this idea of being able to arbitrate and the Arbitration Act doesn't apply.","start":1225.551,"stop":1233.353,"duration":7.8},{"text":"Now the Circuit Court decides --","start":1233.353,"stop":1235.196,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] in the Arbitration Act that defines in commerce is in some statute that matters which affect interstate commerce.","start":1235.196,"stop":1244.316,"duration":9.12}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1244.316,"stop":1244.721,"duration":0.4},{"text":"It doesn't have, as broad definition as does in the -- in a number of these other acts.","start":1244.721,"stop":1249.064,"duration":4.34}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the ground you're arguing on that contract?","start":1249.064,"stop":1252.696,"duration":3.63}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1252.696,"stop":1252.756,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You're arguing that the arbitration -- that this is not subject to the Arbitration Act because you're purely local plumbing contractor was not in commerce between the states?","start":1252.756,"stop":1264.23,"duration":11.47}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"I am arguing that, Mr. Justice --","start":1264.23,"stop":1266.727,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That was raised from the beginning?","start":1266.727,"stop":1269.632,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but I am arguing that even if we are in commerce that it doesn't --","start":1269.632,"stop":1273.958,"duration":4.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that, but you're arguing both?","start":1273.958,"stop":1275.919,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1275.919,"stop":1277.245,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1277.245,"stop":1284.531,"duration":7.29}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"There is an addition to the contract providing that the certain Act would be observed as I recall it and I assume that they were, although there's another case which my brother in the opposition cite where the same -- where Your Honor has set to labor brought an injunction suit against them to --","start":1284.531,"stop":1306.132,"duration":21.6}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1306.132,"stop":1307.304,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Because they weren't complying with it at the time --","start":1307.304,"stop":1309.628,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1309.628,"stop":1321.412,"duration":11.78}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"It's in your name, Your Honor.","start":1321.412,"stop":1322.616,"duration":1.2},{"text":"It's Goldberg versus Electronic Missile Facilities or [Inaudible] Construction Corporation that used to be known as --","start":1322.616,"stop":1328.56,"duration":5.94}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That was under the Court, Bacon-Davis Act, the contract --","start":1328.56,"stop":1331.772,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"I think Fair Labor Standards Act what they were talking to violating is my recollection.","start":1331.772,"stop":1336.357,"duration":4.59}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Was that under the law which provides that whether a thing is local or interstate, a contractor making a contract to the United States must observe certain rules?","start":1336.357,"stop":1348.486,"duration":12.13},{"text":"Is that the law that's on there?","start":1348.486,"stop":1350.998,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know if it's under that law, Your Honor.","start":1350.998,"stop":1352.852,"duration":1.85},{"text":"The cases that I'm referring to was merely as I understand an injunction against violating the Fair Labor Standards Act for failing to pay the minimum wages and overtime is a suit that we were put to that being cited in respondents' brief.","start":1352.852,"stop":1366.91,"duration":14.06}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose the federal government wouldn't have had any power to act in that area at this point in interstate commerce, wouldn't that be true?","start":1366.91,"stop":1375.409,"duration":8.5}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then that certainly had to be holding that company was engaged in it on that particular project which was not this one we're talking about.","start":1375.409,"stop":1383.223,"duration":7.81},{"text":"And I think there's a great distinction between the case there involved where they were building something to be added to some base that was already there.","start":1383.223,"stop":1391.642,"duration":8.42},{"text":"And this Court has clearly held when you building an addition to existing facilities already engaged in commerce that then that construction work comes within it but they haven't ever overruled so far as I know or modified the decision where it says, where as purely new -- brand new construction and not an addition to an existing facility that is not covered by the Fair Labor Standards Act.","start":1391.642,"stop":1418.976,"duration":27.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well whatever that was, the Fair Laborer Standards Act sets up one thing for determining whether the thing is in commerce within the meaning of that Act --","start":1418.976,"stop":1428.301,"duration":9.32}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1428.301,"stop":1428.719,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And the Arbitration Act sets up another?","start":1428.719,"stop":1431.211,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, Your Honor.","start":1431.211,"stop":1432.064,"duration":0.85},{"text":"The Fair Labors Standards Act has long definition including communications and various other things whereas the Arbitrations Act defines commerce as herein defined, means commerce among the sale of states so far a nation or in any territory of the United States or in District of Columbia, or between one territory or another and so forth.","start":1432.064,"stop":1450.647,"duration":18.58},{"text":"It doesn't have all these other ramifications of affecting commerce --","start":1450.647,"stop":1454.834,"duration":4.19}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It doesn't have the ramifications to put an act, wanted to take advantage of the full sweep of the Freeport doctrine.","start":1454.834,"stop":1462.434,"duration":7.6},{"text":"That a -- it -- it's enough for Congress to take jurisdiction under the statute to say that it affects commerce.","start":1462.434,"stop":1468.733,"duration":6.3}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it did not incorporate that.","start":1468.733,"stop":1470.424,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It does not go that far, doesn't it?","start":1470.424,"stop":1471.738,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1471.738,"stop":1472.609,"duration":0.87},{"text":"And it provides it -- provision in a maritime transaction all contract evidencing transactions --","start":1472.609,"stop":1478.034,"duration":5.43}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But this is not a maritime transaction, is it?","start":1478.034,"stop":1480.241,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I've reading the language or contract evidencing of the transaction involving commerce is what the Act applies to, but in getting to the point of whether or not the man signed the contract with that provision in there and he did.","start":1480.241,"stop":1498.394,"duration":18.15},{"text":"I was pointing out that this Act applies not just to subcontractors who are plumbing and heating men but to day laborers, men who out there pushing a shovel for Electronic and Missile Facilities, all for the subcontractor and everybody else who's furnishing material.","start":1498.394,"stop":1513.017,"duration":14.62},{"text":"It applies to every single laborer and materialmen and if the Electronic and Missile Facilities can get up a planted subcontract form of that kind and require every subcontractor who deals with them to sign on that form, then by the same token they can require every laborer who is on their payroll to sign an agreement that any dispute we got or any claim for unpaid wages will be brought not as the Miller Act says, but up in New York, put to be arbitrated, every laborer can be required to sign that.","start":1513.017,"stop":1546.285,"duration":33.27},{"text":"It can require every subcontractor as a part of this planted thing they make him sign to get that kind of agreement from all the laborers who work for him and furnish it to the prime contractor that every claim of any laborer against the subcontractor it must be brought in New York.","start":1546.285,"stop":1561.396,"duration":15.11},{"text":"They can require that subcontractor to get a similar agreement from every person who furnishes material to that subcontractor, but they can go further, if it please the Court.","start":1561.396,"stop":1571.653,"duration":10.26},{"text":"The --","start":1571.653,"stop":1571.909,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"The subcontractor [Inaudible]","start":1571.909,"stop":1578.257,"duration":6.35}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"There's nothing in the record on that, Your Honor.","start":1578.257,"stop":1580.746,"duration":2.49},{"text":"I -- certainly it was not represented by me at that time.","start":1580.746,"stop":1585.009,"duration":4.26},{"text":"I understand that the he had some lawyer to phrase for him the writing that's on the last page setting out what he is to do.","start":1585.009,"stop":1594.369,"duration":9.36},{"text":"This really set out and I don't know if the evidence will show the lawyer saw this thing.","start":1594.369,"stop":1598.326,"duration":3.96},{"text":"It was to be added to but put in the words from these other things that it was not covered.","start":1598.326,"stop":1605.427,"duration":7.1}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1605.427,"stop":1611.173,"duration":5.75}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"The rate or the amounts were about $200,000 in each place, Your Honor.","start":1611.173,"stop":1614.469,"duration":3.3},{"text":"About $400,000 there are various extras and various other work that was done to bring the total up to sum about what Your Honor mentioned.","start":1614.469,"stop":1621.731,"duration":7.26}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1621.731,"stop":1628.501,"duration":6.77}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll see it now -- I don't want you on a misapprehension.","start":1628.501,"stop":1631.938,"duration":3.44},{"text":"You didn't bring one -- I think in the work they were doing down in Georgia.","start":1631.938,"stop":1636.003,"duration":4.06},{"text":"It was somewhere off in Puerto Rico.","start":1636.003,"stop":1637.632,"duration":1.63},{"text":"It hasn't got anything to do with this case.","start":1637.632,"stop":1639.046,"duration":1.41},{"text":"I say it was different type of work.","start":1639.046,"stop":1641.052,"duration":2.01},{"text":"Here they are building a brand new missile facility, out there in the country where there's nothing before.","start":1641.052,"stop":1646.744,"duration":5.69},{"text":"It's 20 miles from the base.","start":1646.744,"stop":1649.034,"duration":2.29},{"text":"In the one way, Your Honor brought the suit, they were adding something to a base in Puerto Rico as I understand.","start":1649.034,"stop":1654.501,"duration":5.47},{"text":"They were adding something to a place already in existence.","start":1654.501,"stop":1657.489,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Not this one?","start":1657.489,"stop":1658.252,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Not this one at all.","start":1658.252,"stop":1659.27,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1659.27,"stop":1665.204,"duration":5.93}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Not my client.","start":1665.204,"stop":1666.37,"duration":1.17},{"text":"These folks I'm suing the Elec -- Electronic -- Yes, the prime contractor, Electronic and Missile Facilities, they do business all around.","start":1666.37,"stop":1674.405,"duration":8.04},{"text":"We allege in this complaint that they are nothing but brokers, that they don't have any of workmen themselves.","start":1674.405,"stop":1681.813,"duration":7.41},{"text":"They get a job and they palm it out in subcontract every single item of it and require every subcontractor to whom they have served it to sign one of these forms.","start":1681.813,"stop":1692.594,"duration":10.78},{"text":"And I say it if they can --","start":1692.594,"stop":1693.712,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean that you have alleged in this charge you make that they do not have any people to do this at work that they contract to do?","start":1693.712,"stop":1703.673,"duration":9.96}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I, I allege that they -- there is a time they got the contract and entered into the contract with Mr. Mosley, that they had no intention of performing the proper function of a general contract of supervising and coordinating the work of the various subcontractors.","start":1703.673,"stop":1718.981,"duration":15.31},{"text":"But if they subcontracted every single item of the work and that they went so far is to lay -- and sweeping out a building to prorate the cost of doing that between all of the subcontractors on the job.","start":1718.981,"stop":1732.523,"duration":13.54},{"text":"It ostensibly but that in fact they charged the total cost of sweeping out a building to every single one to subcontractors.","start":1732.523,"stop":1739.552,"duration":7.03},{"text":"We allege that, we allege that it's a fraudulent scheme from beginning to end to obtain work and materials without paying for it or if they had to pay anything to browbeat the people who worked for them down to taking less than they had earned in order to avoid going off to New York and arbitrate.","start":1739.552,"stop":1754.968,"duration":15.42},{"text":"And that one of the means by which they intended to carry this scheme into effect was this arbitration provision that's in here.","start":1754.968,"stop":1762.406,"duration":7.44}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And what does the Court of Appeals do with that?","start":1762.406,"stop":1765.514,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"The Court of Appeals say we haven't alleged how we going to be hurt.","start":1765.514,"stop":1768.67,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But in the [Inaudible]","start":1768.67,"stop":1770.396,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"How are we going to be hurt by arbitration in New York instead of trying in the District Court in Macon, Georgia although, it's decided on the pleadings and we make the allegations in the pleading of this fraudulent schemes and we make the allegation that we could not properly prevent our plan before an arbitration panel in New York for reasons that I've already mentioned.","start":1770.396,"stop":1794.235,"duration":23.84},{"text":"And this Court has had occasion to point out very distinctly the difference in the substantive rights of the parties that may result from proceeding by arbitration rather in the court of law and that was done in the case of Barnhart versus Polygraphic Company in hundredth law edition when I use it refer to 350 U.S. that is the recent decision.","start":1794.235,"stop":1825.182,"duration":30.95},{"text":"They rendered it by arbitration, whatever its merits or shortcomings, it substantially affects the cause of action, the nature of the tribunal where a suit is tried is a -- is an important part of the parcel of rights behind the cause of action. Change from a court of law to an arbitration panel may make a radical difference and ultimate results.","start":1825.182,"stop":1844.091,"duration":18.91},{"text":"And in no point in my reading further from that that's in the brief but I wanted to invite the Court's attention this time to the fact there is such a radical difference in the substantive rights in the final outcome between whether you travel by a court suit or by arbitration.","start":1844.091,"stop":1861.768,"duration":17.68},{"text":"And then they ask the court to consider the language of the Miller Act itself when we are talking about the background of it and the Heard Act in its deficiencies permitting people to be delayed who were entitled to their money and the fact that Congress intended to correct that deficiency by enactment of the Miller Act, and then that they put into it language that won't be found in any other statute.","start":1861.768,"stop":1884.932,"duration":23.16},{"text":"And I think it's significant that in this case, in the brief of respondent just as in the Circuit Court opinion, they dwell at length doing that part of the Miller Act which says that every suit shall be brought in the United States District Court of the district in which work were to be performed and not elsewhere, but the brief of respondent doesn't text these words which to me are unequivocal.","start":1884.932,"stop":1908.976,"duration":24.04},{"text":"It's set out that they keep me stay because they say if a man had -- the act itself says every person, and we're talking about laborers, subcontractor, materialmen who is furnished labor and material and who hadn't been paid in 90 days shall have the right to sue on such payment bond for the amount or the balance they have unpaid at the time of the institution [Inaudible] and to prosecute said action to final execution in judgment for the sum or sums just and due to him.","start":1908.976,"stop":1938.901,"duration":29.92},{"text":"Now if Congress had every intended that you had a right to sue but after [Inaudible] suit, you had to set it aside and let it be stayed while you ran off up to New York and arbitrate, if it eventuated in search result then those words would have been put in there, they would have stop by saying, “Shall have the right sue”.","start":1938.901,"stop":1956.199,"duration":17.3}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But the word might sometime become a part of the judgment of the court, wouldn't it?","start":1956.199,"stop":1962.849,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"It might, Your Honor.","start":1962.849,"stop":1964.212,"duration":1.36},{"text":"And they could have accomplished that result by simply saying he shall have the right to sue.","start":1964.212,"stop":1969.381,"duration":5.17},{"text":"But to evidence the fact that that suit was to go forward and not to be sidetracked to stop.","start":1969.381,"stop":1974.551,"duration":5.17},{"text":"They added the words, “And prosecute set action to final execution of the judgment.”","start":1974.551,"stop":1978.722,"duration":4.17},{"text":"And prosecute means to carry on, it means the exact opposite of stay.","start":1978.722,"stop":1982.895,"duration":4.17},{"text":"To stay a suit means wait a while as I use to say in the country stay means wait and prosecute means carry on or get up as we said to amicus.","start":1982.895,"stop":1994.089,"duration":11.19},{"text":"They're the exact opposite.","start":1994.089,"stop":1995.082,"duration":0.99},{"text":"You can't prosecute it to a final execution excuse in judgment if it stayed and those words were deliberately inserted by Congress.","start":1995.082,"stop":2004.905,"duration":9.82},{"text":"Because in not any of act, they weren't in Heard Act, they would try to overcome difficulties and they put this words which we must say Congress intended to have a meaning.","start":2004.905,"stop":2014.328,"duration":9.42}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well is this just non-waivable provision in your view?","start":2014.328,"stop":2018.546,"duration":4.22}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"None, what?","start":2018.546,"stop":2019.255,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Non-waivable provision.","start":2019.255,"stop":2021.116,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2021.116,"stop":2021.676,"duration":0.56},{"text":"That -- that's my exact point, that a man can't waive those.","start":2021.676,"stop":2025.933,"duration":4.26},{"text":"And we cite in the brief a number of cases where this Court has held and where a new right is created by Congress in the public interest, in those to private right.","start":2025.933,"stop":2037.024,"duration":11.09},{"text":"That that private right cannot be waived where to do so would thwart the purpose of Congress.","start":2037.024,"stop":2043.387,"duration":6.36},{"text":"And it's our contention that Congress intended that people be paid who do work on Government contracts.","start":2043.387,"stop":2049.132,"duration":5.75},{"text":"And that they not be put off, so that they'll have financial pressure applied and have to settle for less but that they be paid promptly.","start":2049.132,"stop":2055.987,"duration":6.86},{"text":"That's a provision of the bond that they would be paid promptly and they provide this solvent surety in order that they won't be insolvency to confront them.","start":2055.987,"stop":2067.934,"duration":11.95}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Generally speaking, a lawsuit in the District Court would give you prompter relief and arbitration would?","start":2067.934,"stop":2077.223,"duration":9.29}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2077.223,"stop":2078.231,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you?","start":2078.231,"stop":2080.435,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Because we, we have alleged that we can't prevent these issues before an arbitration panel.","start":2080.435,"stop":2086.761,"duration":6.33},{"text":"And this Court has pointed out that arbitrators are not in conversant with the law.","start":2086.761,"stop":2091.406,"duration":4.64},{"text":"They wouldn't know what to do with this allegation of fraud we've got.","start":2091.406,"stop":2095.695,"duration":4.29},{"text":"If it was a simple question of the term that whether the old 490,000 or 472,000 an arbitrator might decide, but an arbitration panel could not determine and I say this question as to whether the defendant, prime contractor acting with such fraud in entering into a contract, he had no intention of performing as to entitle as to rescind that contract.","start":2095.695,"stop":2119.354,"duration":23.66},{"text":"That's a fairly complicated legal issue that I say arbitration --","start":2119.354,"stop":2125.037,"duration":5.68}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"What kind of an arbitration panel does the agreement provide for?","start":2125.037,"stop":2131.596,"duration":6.56}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"It provides that it be done before -- in accordance with the practice of the Supreme Court of New York, it's on page 42 of the record, the provision of the contract with respect that.","start":2131.596,"stop":2144.486,"duration":12.89},{"text":"Any controversy or claim arising out of or relating to this agreement or the briefs thereof and I point out that it doesn't have to -- you don't have to have any dispute, you just have to have a claim, say they owe you some money.","start":2144.486,"stop":2157.054,"duration":12.57},{"text":"Provision for the termination of which not made elsewhere in this agreement, shall be settled by arbitration in the Borough of Manhattan City in the State of New York in accordance with the Civil Practice Act in the State of New York and then they go on to provide another in the event that will work some other kind of arbitration by the American Arbitration Association.","start":2157.054,"stop":2176.619,"duration":19.57},{"text":"In subparagraph (c) they purport to provide that either party can bring in other parties.","start":2176.619,"stop":2182.218,"duration":5.6},{"text":"Now whether they try to incorporate in this, what is the equivalent of a third party plaintiff in defendant proceeding in the civil procedure of the federal courts.","start":2182.218,"stop":2194.919,"duration":12.7}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2194.919,"stop":2215.688,"duration":20.77}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Some of them do have that kind.","start":2215.688,"stop":2217.446,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] that this provision for trial in the District Court under the Miller Act is not waivable.","start":2217.446,"stop":2228.822,"duration":11.38},{"text":"Is there anything in the Miller Act in the way of a provision to comparable of those provisions that much?","start":2228.822,"stop":2234.402,"duration":5.58}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"There is not a provision specifically prohibiting waiver of the rights.","start":2234.402,"stop":2240.317,"duration":5.91}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't attach any significance to that on the question whether this right is waivable?","start":2240.317,"stop":2245.983,"duration":5.67}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't for two reasons if I may answer that way, Mr. Justice Brennan.","start":2245.983,"stop":2252.88,"duration":6.9},{"text":"First, the language that they shall have the right to prosecute it, to final action and judgment is so clear to me that it can't be stopped, that it's opposite of being stayed that it weren't necessary to put that in.","start":2252.88,"stop":2266.585,"duration":13.7},{"text":"But secondly, under the decision of this Court in Brooklyn Savings Bank versus O'Neil, where the same argument was made with respect of the Fair Labors Standards Act, that these other acts had prohibitions against waiving different things.","start":2266.585,"stop":2279.712,"duration":13.13},{"text":"And if this one didn't and this Court says absence of such provisions has not prevented the Court from invalidating waiver where the legislative policy would be brought in by permitting such contracts.","start":2279.712,"stop":2293.137,"duration":13.43},{"text":"The decision is to the case is based on the legislative policy behind the enactment.","start":2293.137,"stop":2297.868,"duration":4.73},{"text":"And that were said in answer to an argument, that this Fair Labor Standards Act did not contain this prohibition against waiver that was in these other acts to which Your Honor referred.","start":2297.868,"stop":2307.582,"duration":9.71},{"text":"But the Court answered it by saying if the legislative policy is clear and would be voided by the kind of waiver that the parties have attempted to agree to then we just won't permit it.","start":2307.582,"stop":2316.63,"duration":9.05},{"text":"If it violates, it thwarts the purpose of Congress and that's our contention here.","start":2316.63,"stop":2321.604,"duration":4.97},{"text":"It's two-fold.","start":2321.604,"stop":2322.889,"duration":1.29},{"text":"It's so clear in the Miller Act that they didn't need to say it.","start":2322.889,"stop":2326.566,"duration":3.68},{"text":"Certainly if you can develop a policy with that respect to some prohibition, it doesn't have to be in there and that this Court has said so in that case.","start":2326.566,"stop":2336.763,"duration":10.2}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there such a provision in the Wage and Hour Act?","start":2336.763,"stop":2340.252,"duration":3.49}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"There was not in this Fair Labor Standards Act --","start":2340.252,"stop":2344.217,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"In the Fair Labor Standards Act?","start":2344.217,"stop":2344.906,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"-- according to that decision.","start":2344.906,"stop":2349.174,"duration":4.27},{"text":"In that case it was argued that Congress did not intend for such a waive of rights to be void because it had in other acts specifically provided, that waive of rights there granted would be void but had not so provided in this Act.","start":2349.174,"stop":2360.507,"duration":11.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What was held?","start":2360.507,"stop":2361.514,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"And in rejecting this contention this Court said, “Absence of such provision however has not prevented the Court from invalidating waivers, where the legislative policy would be thwarted by permitting such contracts.”","start":2361.514,"stop":2374.079,"duration":12.57},{"text":"The decision in the instant case is based on the legislative policy behind this enactment and there the waiver was signed after all rights had accrued, which to my mind is a tremendous difference between waiving all your rights in advance under the Fair Labor Standards Act there dealt with in that case.","start":2374.079,"stop":2394.485,"duration":20.41},{"text":"The time had been worked for which the man should have been paid more money and over time.","start":2394.485,"stop":2399.741,"duration":5.26},{"text":"And they had paid him all of that and at that time had got him to agree to waive the overtime provisions and so forth.","start":2399.741,"stop":2407.416,"duration":7.68},{"text":"And the court said even though the rights had accrued, he couldn't waive them even though the statute doesn't say you can't waive them.","start":2407.416,"stop":2414.111,"duration":6.69},{"text":"But it is for the purpose of the Act, it would violate the policy that Congress had in mind if you were permitted to waive.","start":2414.111,"stop":2420.067,"duration":5.96}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is you argument on this point that this in short, and I want to see if I understand it, that the Miller Act was passed in order to solicitude, to take care of the people who supplied work and material in construction work and things of that kind that it expressly gave them the right to file a suit in the courts of law and that if you apply the Arbitration Act so as to defy them of that right to file a suit as far away at least at the City of New York and South Georgia that it will impose various on the, on the right that Congress intended to give the workers and the contractors by the Miller Act?","start":2420.067,"stop":2465.71,"duration":45.64},{"text":"Is that the argument you're making?","start":2465.71,"stop":2466.294,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's the argument I'm making, except that I'm emphasizing or undertaking to do so that Congress didn't stop with just giving them the right to sue, but that they specifically said they shall have the right to prosecute that action to final execution and judgment, which to my mind means they had in mind the provisions of arbitration law which was passed ten years before then and saying that this suit is not one to be stayed.","start":2466.294,"stop":2488.86,"duration":22.57},{"text":"It's to be prosecuted to final execution and judgment that that's the only difference I make between Your Honor's statement of what I am trying to argue and the way Your Honor stated.","start":2488.86,"stop":2497.462,"duration":8.6}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2497.462,"stop":2507.155,"duration":9.69}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it does.","start":2507.155,"stop":2508.063,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2508.063,"stop":2514.183,"duration":6.12}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well if were applied though, Your Honor our suit would sit down in the District Court in Macon instead of being prompt to tried, it was set and we go off to New York and I don't know how long it would take to resolve all these issues there and then get it reduced to an award and come back to the District Court in Macon, Georgia and ask them for a judgment based on this award that was obtained.","start":2514.183,"stop":2536.554,"duration":22.37},{"text":"And if we succeeded before the arbitration panel in establishing our contention that the whole contract was fraudulent and then therefore void then the arbitration panel would have to stop at making that finding then we come back to the District Court and try the whole case over.","start":2536.554,"stop":2550.796,"duration":14.24}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2550.796,"stop":2571.055,"duration":20.26}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well because of my contention that an arbitration panel is not instructed in the law.","start":2571.055,"stop":2576.521,"duration":5.47},{"text":"They don't have instructions on the law.","start":2576.521,"stop":2578.772,"duration":2.25},{"text":"There's no judge to tell them what the law is with respect to a particular set of facts.","start":2578.772,"stop":2584.318,"duration":5.55},{"text":"And that's been pointed out by the decisions of this Court, that that makes the substantive difference between the rights of parties proceeding in a court and proceeding before an arbitration panel.","start":2584.318,"stop":2592.537,"duration":8.22},{"text":"They might decide that [Inaudible] or not.","start":2592.537,"stop":2595.215,"duration":2.68},{"text":"There's no judge there to tell them that if there this certain prompt doesn't the contract is that to me.","start":2595.215,"stop":2600.548,"duration":5.33},{"text":"They are layman, they're not learned in the law and there's no way to make that point properly speaking to an Arbitration Board is what I am contending.","start":2600.548,"stop":2609.573,"duration":9.03}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2609.573,"stop":2617.297,"duration":7.72}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well in that view I'm adopting the language of this Court, pointing out that distinct.","start":2617.297,"stop":2625.296,"duration":8},{"text":"I think wherever it's important that the law be applied, complicated legal issues be determined as opposed to simple fact issues that you do have that difficulty in an arbitration.","start":2625.296,"stop":2639.152,"duration":13.86}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"One of the purposes of the Miller Act, wasn't it, was to make it easy to employees with work contracted with them by contract easily going to court and enforce their claim?","start":2639.152,"stop":2649.716,"duration":10.56}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's been repeatedly pointed by the decisions of this Court and of the Circuit Courts.","start":2649.716,"stop":2653.472,"duration":3.76},{"text":"That was purpose of it to make it easier, to overcome these delays that result under the Heard Act where --","start":2653.472,"stop":2659.725,"duration":6.25}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] that thing that they have to go to New York or to London and arbitrations are required would put pretty big burden on people?","start":2659.725,"stop":2667.871,"duration":8.15}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2667.871,"stop":2668.681,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] prior of the trial at the place where the thing incurred.","start":2668.681,"stop":2674.325,"duration":5.64}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's exactly how our contention, may it please the Court.","start":2674.325,"stop":2679.553,"duration":5.23},{"text":"And there -- if I can quickly name these fats that would be result from permitting arbitrations to have a suit, first place the surety is not bound by the arbitration, he's not a party to it.","start":2679.553,"stop":2693.121,"duration":13.57},{"text":"You might participate in an arbitration to get an award and the surety that won't pay it then you got to sue in the District Court, still nevertheless the surety can litigate the same issues all over again.","start":2693.121,"stop":2704.278,"duration":11.16},{"text":"And yet if you lose before the arbitration panel, you are concluded and you got no claim left against the surety, that's one important thing -- distinction.","start":2704.278,"stop":2713.482,"duration":9.2},{"text":"The second is that there's a time limit in the Miller Act of one year from the last days you furnish material or labor within which your suit in the District Court must be brought --","start":2713.482,"stop":2722.023,"duration":8.54}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Just going back, going back to your first point, why couldn't the surety be a part to the arbitration under the agreement that you make?","start":2722.023,"stop":2726.947,"duration":4.92}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"He is not a part of the contract.","start":2726.947,"stop":2728.843,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It would be agreement provides that other parties can be brought into the arbitration?","start":2728.843,"stop":2735.827,"duration":6.98}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, but I don't -- I don't see how that could possibly be enforced as against another party who was not for it.","start":2735.827,"stop":2741.845,"duration":6.02}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly party or the party affected the surety I'm talking about.","start":2741.845,"stop":2747.203,"duration":5.36},{"text":"However if that's --","start":2747.203,"stop":2748.163,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I mean this is in New York and I don't know if that surety is up there, that New York could have got a jurisdiction of that surety.","start":2748.163,"stop":2754.259,"duration":6.1},{"text":"And certainly he and I can agree that a New York court got jurisdiction to somebody else, who is not up there, I mean who is not a part of that contract.","start":2754.259,"stop":2763.326,"duration":9.07}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"The point there is that the surety bond, they have no such provision?","start":2763.326,"stop":2769.282,"duration":5.96}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"The surety bond?","start":2769.282,"stop":2770.787,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"They have no provision for arbitration?","start":2770.787,"stop":2773.77,"duration":2.98}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"It's required to have the provision set out by the statute, if it please the Court.","start":2773.77,"stop":2778.109,"duration":4.34},{"text":"And there is even a regulations setting out the very wedding of a bond, running to the United States of America.","start":2778.109,"stop":2785.612,"duration":7.5},{"text":"I mentioned there's a time limit within which you must bring a suit to the District Court, that's one year.","start":2785.612,"stop":2790.517,"duration":4.9},{"text":"And a man must bring a suit even if you say it can be stayed for arbitration because his time would run out while he's off somewhere arbitrating.","start":2790.517,"stop":2800.284,"duration":9.77},{"text":"Therefore, he's got to go to New York.","start":2800.284,"stop":2801.761,"duration":1.48},{"text":"He's got to hire two sets of lawyer, one in Macon, Georgia and some more in New York to handle the arbitration provision.","start":2801.761,"stop":2808.757,"duration":7},{"text":"I have mentioned that if this were valid the prime contractor could require every laborer to sign the similar agreement and could require his subcontractor to get a similar agreement from everyone, his laborers and materialmen.","start":2808.757,"stop":2820.079,"duration":11.32},{"text":"And that the surety could impose as a requirement for his writing the bond that the prime contract to punish him such agreement from all the subs and all materialmen of off's and so forth.","start":2820.079,"stop":2834.197,"duration":14.12},{"text":"Finally, this is a suit by the United States.","start":2834.197,"stop":2837.954,"duration":3.76},{"text":"It's not a suit just by motive.","start":2837.954,"stop":2840.917,"duration":2.96},{"text":"It was decided under the Heard Act which preceded this.","start":2840.917,"stop":2844.889,"duration":3.97},{"text":"That the United States itself is so much interested in the preservation and protection of the rights granted by the statute that it is not just a nominal, but a real point to such a suit brought in the name of the United States for the use of the materialmen.","start":2844.889,"stop":2860.633,"duration":15.74},{"text":"That was held in the United States Fidelity and Guaranty Company versus United States of America and I'm sorry this case is not on my brief in 204 U.S. 349 where this Court pointed out the United States is not here nearly no -- nominal or formal party.","start":2860.633,"stop":2878.014,"duration":17.38},{"text":"Although this was a suit on the Heard Act just like this.","start":2878.014,"stop":2881.037,"duration":3.02},{"text":"It has the legal right.","start":2881.037,"stop":2882.825,"duration":1.79},{"text":"It was a principle party to the contract and in view of the words of the statute maybe said to have an interest in the performance of all of its provisions.","start":2882.825,"stop":2890.766,"duration":7.94},{"text":"It maybe that the interest of the Government has involved in the construction of public works will be [Inaudible] if contracts to this for such works are able to obtain materials and supplies with certainty and prompt, to that end Congress may have been that important to assure those who furnish such material or supplies that the Government would exert its power directly for their protection.","start":2890.766,"stop":2912.278,"duration":21.51},{"text":"It may well have thought that the Government was under some obligation to guard the interest of those whose labor and materials would go into a public building.","start":2912.278,"stop":2921.441,"duration":9.16},{"text":"That same thing applicable to the Heard Act is even more applicable to the Miller Act because this Court has said the reason for the Miller Act was to remove some of these procedural difficulties and to make it easier for unpaid laborers and materialmen to realize the benefit of this bond.","start":2921.441,"stop":2937.999,"duration":16.56},{"text":"One of the Circuit Courts has characterized a bond on which you can't sue as being an empty gesture and a [Inaudible] carried out by the contractor in the surety of public expense and that certainly would be true as to the bond here.","start":2937.999,"stop":2953.504,"duration":15.51},{"text":"If we can't sue the surety but must go up to New York and engage in an arbitration fight with the prime.","start":2953.504,"stop":2960.074,"duration":6.57},{"text":"I would like to reserve what time I have for rebuttal.","start":2960.074,"stop":2962.833,"duration":2.76}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You may.","start":2962.833,"stop":2968.583,"duration":5.75},{"text":"Mr. Edenfield?","start":2968.583,"stop":2970.128,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, members of the Court.","start":2970.128,"stop":2977.263,"duration":7.13},{"text":"In undertaking to prepare myself for this argument, I think I played a little guessing game that I am sure that have done before me, tried to guess what question it was that caused certiorari to be granted in this case.","start":2977.263,"stop":2994.536,"duration":17.27},{"text":"I am still not at all sure, so I can only address myself if the Court please to the matters which have been made by opposing counsel in their brief and to such questions that may have been asked while he was addressing the Court.","start":2994.536,"stop":3014.843,"duration":20.31},{"text":"Several things --","start":3014.843,"stop":3015.612,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I say this that in order to – we will probably not finish this afternoon and before you have finished, I'd like you to consider a question of jurisdiction raised by Section 4 of the Arbitration Act, which as I read it, gives no court jurisdiction to import arbitration except in the district that a suit can be filed and where the arbitration has to take place.","start":3015.612,"stop":3042.535,"duration":26.92}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court there is one federal case and I don't believe it came from this Court, where that question was raised as concerns the question whether or not the enforcement would take place in New York, where the arbitration took place or in a District Court where the suit was filed.","start":3042.535,"stop":3059.926,"duration":17.39},{"text":"And it was sort of equivocal on it but I understood the holding to be that in a proper case notwithstanding that they could enforce it in whether -- back in Macon, Georgia.","start":3059.926,"stop":3072.947,"duration":13.02}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But I was, I was referring not to any case but to the Section itself which I may say at this time as I read it would limit the right to enforce an arbitration agreement in Georgia to the district in which the suit could be filed in the District Court and it could only enforce an arbitration in that district and not in New York by any part for arbitration.","start":3072.947,"stop":3102.735,"duration":29.79}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought that this would be the proper way it would be handled.","start":3102.735,"stop":3107.443,"duration":4.71},{"text":"That the suit in the District Court which is brought in the proper district pursuant to the Miller Act would be stayed as the Arbitration Act provides pending arbitration.","start":3107.443,"stop":3117.885,"duration":10.44},{"text":"Once arbitration had taken place, this -- the award will then come back to the District Court in Macon to be enforced which --","start":3117.885,"stop":3126.021,"duration":8.14}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] the one to call your attention --","start":3126.021,"stop":3127.58,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":3127.58,"stop":3127.918,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"So if you decide to discuss it, you'd have ample opportunity to do so because to me it is important jurisdictional point in the case.","start":3127.918,"stop":3135.737,"duration":7.82}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll try to ask comment but more.","start":3135.737,"stop":3138.388,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":3138.388,"stop":3149.551,"duration":11.16}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that is not my question.","start":3149.551,"stop":3151.735,"duration":2.18},{"text":"My question is whether or not Section 4 provides where the suit can be filed to enforce the arbitration by the only place that can be enforced and gives that court jurisdiction only to require arbitration within that judicial district.","start":3151.735,"stop":3171.014,"duration":19.28}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, the arbitration division in this contract has brought enough to prevent for mid arbitration anyway.","start":3171.014,"stop":3178.016,"duration":7}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand about the contract.","start":3178.016,"stop":3179.555,"duration":1.54},{"text":"I'm talking about the statute, Section 4 of the Arbitration Act.","start":3179.555,"stop":3185.333,"duration":5.78}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Well if it can be arbitrated anywhere if the Court please, I see no obstacle to be enforced in the Middle District of Georgia.","start":3185.333,"stop":3191.866,"duration":6.53}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well that, that -- you still do not get the question I pose which is, I'd like you to have so you could discuss it in the morning.","start":3191.866,"stop":3201.297,"duration":9.43},{"text":"As I read the Arbitration Act, you cannot make a valid contract to arbitrate under it which will be enforceable in a court, except in the district --","start":3201.297,"stop":3212.162,"duration":10.86}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, you mean the entering --","start":3212.162,"stop":3214.823,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] and it has to take place and that is the arbitration.","start":3214.823,"stop":3219.339,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright sir, I'll discuss it tomorrow.","start":3219.339,"stop":3221.085,"duration":1.75},{"text":"But I may go on to some of the question raised here this afternoon.","start":3221.085,"stop":3226.362,"duration":5.28},{"text":"The question was raised whether or not the stand of the fraud alleged in this contract and whether or not there was any over reaching of the parties in certain arbitration provision.","start":3226.362,"stop":3238.99,"duration":12.63},{"text":"The only fraud claimed in that connection is that the contractor maliciously inserted an arbitration provision.","start":3238.99,"stop":3247.125,"duration":8.14}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"You just say action for a re-seizure in the contract?","start":3247.125,"stop":3249.847,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, this is under an action for a seizure.","start":3249.847,"stop":3252.733,"duration":2.89},{"text":"I'll discuss that, that was one of the question I asked is what I mean at this time.","start":3252.733,"stop":3258.222,"duration":5.49},{"text":"Mr. Justice Black also suggested that there might be an impossibility of requiring someone to go beyond the jurisdiction of the state for the purpose of arbitration.","start":3258.222,"stop":3269.255,"duration":11.03},{"text":"That case -- that question came up in the Second Circuit if the Court please, in the case of Shanferoke Coal Company versus West Chester Service Corporation.","start":3269.255,"stop":3278.889,"duration":9.63},{"text":"It was decided by just Judge Learned Hand that you could require to arbitrate although it required going beyond the jurisdiction of the court and this Court had found it unanimously, if the Court please in the decision by Justice Brandeis.","start":3278.889,"stop":3294.184,"duration":15.3},{"text":"Both of those cases are cited in our brief. Now as far as the question --","start":3294.184,"stop":3299.247,"duration":5.06}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] to go to London, was it?","start":3299.247,"stop":3301.961,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3301.961,"stop":3302.182,"duration":0.22},{"text":"But they said somewhere, Your Honor.","start":3302.182,"stop":3304.176,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3304.176,"stop":3304.675,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the Arbitration Act.","start":3304.675,"stop":3305.71,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":3305.71,"stop":3306.242,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3306.242,"stop":3306.587,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And it's been quite a dispute over among the courts.","start":3306.587,"stop":3308.761,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"There has, yes sir and both of those of course were my maritime transactions.","start":3308.761,"stop":3313.374,"duration":4.61}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":3313.374,"stop":3315.847,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"The two that I referred to in the Second Circuit Shanferoke Coal, S-H-A-N-F-E-R-O-K-E Coal Company versus Westchester Service Corporation.","start":3315.847,"stop":3324.649,"duration":8.8}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":3324.649,"stop":3326.52,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"It was.","start":3326.52,"stop":3327.71,"duration":1.19},{"text":"The same case was unanimously affirmed here it --","start":3327.71,"stop":3331.442,"duration":3.73}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In the brief?","start":3331.442,"stop":3332.398,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it's in the brief.","start":3332.398,"stop":3333.506,"duration":1.11},{"text":"Now let me say this about it in explanation.","start":3333.506,"stop":3336.219,"duration":2.71},{"text":"It was decided prior to Erie versus Tompkins and later in Bernhardt versus Polygraphic, this Court later held that where a diversity case was involved that distinguished from a federal question that arbitration was so substantive that it would have to be governed by a state law, but whether there is a federal question involved, we take the position that Shanferoke is a full based decision of this Court which is still in effect.","start":3336.219,"stop":3362.311,"duration":26.09},{"text":"And in the Circuit Court that Judge Hand held that they would require arbitration even though it would require them to go beyond the jurisdiction on the court.","start":3362.311,"stop":3372.247,"duration":9.94},{"text":"Now as far as whether the transaction here involved was in commerce, of course the Fifth Circuit decided that in our favor and decided the reasons for it not only were the parties here from different states themselves these were the improvements, physical improvements to instrumentalities which were already in commerce, namely two Air Force Bases.","start":3372.247,"stop":3395.707,"duration":23.46},{"text":"These were addition to existing Air Force Bases.","start":3395.707,"stop":3399.143,"duration":3.44},{"text":"Personnel were used and brought across state lines.","start":3399.143,"stop":3402.918,"duration":3.78},{"text":"A subcontractor came from across state lines. Material was brought across state line and in that connection, I might say that the instance in which Mr. Justice Goldberg got after our clients in another context, they were doing precisely the same thing at another Air Force Base and were held to be in commerce.","start":3402.918,"stop":3423.588,"duration":20.67},{"text":"Now at that point, Justice Black made some remarks about the language of the commerce that Arbitration Act being different.","start":3423.588,"stop":3430.251,"duration":6.66},{"text":"I might say that it may as different from the Fair Labor Standards Act but it is in the language if the Court please of the Constitution, Article 1 Section 8 Clause 3.","start":3430.251,"stop":3439.794,"duration":9.54}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Involving commerce?","start":3439.794,"stop":3441.028,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Involving transactions --","start":3441.028,"stop":3443.238,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it says involving commerce.","start":3443.238,"stop":3444.962,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3444.962,"stop":3446.025,"duration":1.06},{"text":"Now as to the question, Judge Black raised about the Davis-Bacon Act, it is incorporated in this contract at the record at page 46.","start":3446.025,"stop":3456.245,"duration":10.22}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":3456.245,"stop":3468.867,"duration":12.62}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3468.867,"stop":3469.182,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":3469.182,"stop":3473.673,"duration":4.49}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3473.673,"stop":3474.391,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] in a District Court.","start":3474.391,"stop":3479.1,"duration":4.71},{"text":"The question I would like to ask you is this [Inaudible] in the Federal District Court [Inaudible] to the New York state court --","start":3479.1,"stop":3511.859,"duration":32.76}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3511.859,"stop":3512.338,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"That you were [Inaudible] arbitration under the New York law.","start":3512.338,"stop":3516.941,"duration":4.6},{"text":"[Inaudible] if that is so doesn't that mean [Inaudible]","start":3516.941,"stop":3561.837,"duration":44.9}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Goldberg, as I understood to you say the first three word of that section are, a person agreed by a failure to arbitrate, is that the way it begins?","start":3561.837,"stop":3571.843,"duration":10.01}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely.","start":3571.843,"stop":3572.628,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"If that is correct then, Your Honor, you see they brought a suit against us in District Court, we asked for a stay pending our arbitration.","start":3572.628,"stop":3581.508,"duration":8.88},{"text":"So we have the matter before the District Court.","start":3581.508,"stop":3584.198,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":3584.198,"stop":3599.445,"duration":15.25}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3599.445,"stop":3599.828,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] whether you have a right under [Inaudible]","start":3599.828,"stop":3623.242,"duration":23.41}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"I can say this, if the Court please as Justice Black has mentioned some of them have been sent to London.","start":3623.242,"stop":3629.651,"duration":6.41},{"text":"There are three physical presences in Circuit Courts where Miller Act cases have been sent elsewhere to be arbitrated.","start":3629.651,"stop":3637.267,"duration":7.62},{"text":"And --","start":3637.267,"stop":3638.158,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":3638.158,"stop":3642.42,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3642.42,"stop":3642.843,"duration":0.42},{"text":"I have to admit there is not.","start":3642.843,"stop":3644.317,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":3644.317,"stop":3650.806,"duration":6.49}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Pending arbitration, yes sir.","start":3650.806,"stop":3652.604,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":3652.604,"stop":3656.971,"duration":4.37}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean to compel and to arbitrate?","start":3656.971,"stop":3659.112,"duration":2.14},{"text":"No, sir that kind hadn't refused to arbitrate.","start":3659.112,"stop":3661.767,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":3661.767,"stop":3665.658,"duration":3.89}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3665.658,"stop":3666.234,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":3666.234,"stop":3668.015,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"We got into court before we could.","start":3668.015,"stop":3670.141,"duration":2.13},{"text":"They have never been --","start":3670.141,"stop":3671.05,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":3671.05,"stop":3683.25,"duration":12.2}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3683.25,"stop":3684.132,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And that the New York order, I mean the Court of Appeals Fifth Circuit has ordered them to go to New York pursuant to a suit you have up there to arbitrate?","start":3684.132,"stop":3696.13,"duration":12}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3696.13,"stop":3696.592,"duration":0.46},{"text":"Now let me say this, Mr. Justice Black, what we did up there for going back to paragraph four or second quote, we were not at that time aggrieved by a failure to arbitrate so as to require us to go into the District Court.","start":3696.592,"stop":3710.04,"duration":13.45},{"text":"There had been no refusal to arbitrate.","start":3710.04,"stop":3712.912,"duration":2.87},{"text":"The dispute came up and at then though refuse to arbitrate, we sought to bring -- to start arbitration, not knowing whether there was going to be a dispute or whether we will be going to be aggrieved or not.","start":3712.912,"stop":3722.681,"duration":9.77}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You filed a lawsuit in New York against the people in Georgia in that service by constructing note?","start":3722.681,"stop":3727.327,"duration":4.65}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, sir.","start":3727.327,"stop":3728.358,"duration":1.03},{"text":"The next thing we know, we went to District Court in the Middle District of Georgia.","start":3728.358,"stop":3733.54,"duration":5.18}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 17, 1963","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren11/oral_argument_audio/14687","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"401, United States for the use of H.W. Moseley doing business as Moseley Plumbing and Heating Company, Petitioner, versus Electronic and Missile Facilities Incorporated.","start":0,"stop":13.484,"duration":13.48},{"text":"Mr. Edenfield, you may continue your argument.","start":13.484,"stop":16.354,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":16.354,"stop":20.817,"duration":4.46},{"text":"On yesterday, Mr. Justice Black asked that I respond this morning to the question whether Section 4 of the United States Arbitration Act relating to the enforcement of arbitration where there had been a refusal to arbitrate does not prevent the type of arbitration here attempted, and specifically, whether Section 4 does not prevent arbitration in Georgia or order of arbitration in Georgia to take place in the State of New York.","start":20.817,"stop":56.253,"duration":35.44}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] in my -- which came first, the lawsuit in Georgia or your arbitration proceeding in New York?","start":56.253,"stop":69.332,"duration":13.08}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Brennan, we gave notice of arbitration pursuant to the agreement in New York.","start":69.332,"stop":74.001,"duration":4.67}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And this was then before --","start":74.001,"stop":74.857,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Thereupon suit was filed by the subcontractor in Georgia.","start":74.857,"stop":79.582,"duration":4.72},{"text":"Thereupon we sought a stay in Georgia pending arbitration in New York.","start":79.582,"stop":84.505,"duration":4.92},{"text":"Those were the order of events.","start":84.505,"stop":85.92,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And then you after that, after you obtained your stay, you then filed a suit in the New York Supreme Court, is that it?","start":85.92,"stop":91.615,"duration":5.69}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, we did not obtain a stay.","start":91.615,"stop":93.559,"duration":1.94},{"text":"As a matter of fact the district judge enjoined us from proceeding in New York and we went to the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals which reversed.","start":93.559,"stop":103.203,"duration":9.64}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"But you have already filed a suit in New York, haven't you?","start":103.203,"stop":105.656,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, we had had served notice pursuant to the New York Civil Practice Act and it had been set down there.","start":105.656,"stop":112.049,"duration":6.39},{"text":"I'm not sure whether you call that filing a suit or not, I'm not familiar with New York arbitration, but we had set it in motion and a hearing had been set, at the time the suit was filed by the subcontractor in Georgia whereupon we were enjoined from proceeding in New York until that was reversed by the Fifth Circuit.","start":112.049,"stop":130.273,"duration":18.22}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And then what did you do in New York?","start":130.273,"stop":132.383,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"We've done nothing because we're still under injunction.","start":132.383,"stop":134.535,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But there's a stay -- there's a stay in --","start":134.535,"stop":135.694,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, no sir the matter is in status quo until --","start":135.694,"stop":141.609,"duration":5.92}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":141.609,"stop":142.079,"duration":0.47},{"text":"Yes, thank you.","start":142.079,"stop":143.893,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"I had not thought on yesterday that Section 4 that any problem was presented under Section 4 because I was on the opinion that we had not yet gotten to Section 4.","start":143.893,"stop":153.783,"duration":9.89},{"text":"We're still trying to get a stay under Section 3 and I was of the opinion that the two sections were rather unrelated.","start":153.783,"stop":162.362,"duration":8.58}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But you cannot get a stay under Section 3 if your arbitration is unenforceable under Section 4?","start":162.362,"stop":170.329,"duration":7.97}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":170.329,"stop":172.729,"duration":2.4},{"text":"I have some authority on that which I'd like to present consisting of a Shanferokee case which I mentioned yesterday.","start":172.729,"stop":181.401,"duration":8.67},{"text":"I think that is the only case where this Court in a full bench decision has ever discussed the relationship between Sections 3 and Section 4 of the Arbitration Act and I believe that decision puts the question at rest.","start":181.401,"stop":196.035,"duration":14.63},{"text":"Now, the Shanferokee case is cited in our brief but it was not cited on this point because the conflict or possible conflict between 3 and 4 was not mentioned or had not been raised until yesterday.","start":196.035,"stop":209.313,"duration":13.28},{"text":"For that reason, I would like to discuss it just a minute and to read what the Court said, what this Court says as to relationship between Sections 3 and Section 4 of the Arbitration Act.","start":209.313,"stop":220.624,"duration":11.31},{"text":"Now Shanferokee, if the Court please, involved an interstate sale of coal.","start":220.624,"stop":226.793,"duration":6.17},{"text":"The defendant was sued by the plaintiff and upon being sued, he sought to pend -- to stay the action pending arbitration.","start":226.793,"stop":235.367,"duration":8.57},{"text":"Now as to what happened in the court below, this Court said and I'm reading from 293 U.S., page 451, this is mere recital of what happened in the District Court.","start":235.367,"stop":246.458,"duration":11.09},{"text":"The District Court interpreted the clause that is the Arbitration Clause as making the arbitration enforceable only in the State Courts of New York and on that ground denied the stay.","start":246.458,"stop":260.158,"duration":13.7},{"text":"On appeal from the order of denial, the Court of Appeals held that even if the clause should be so interpreted, Section 3 of the United States Arbitration Act authorized the stay.","start":260.158,"stop":271.248,"duration":11.09},{"text":"It, therefore, reversed the order and direct to the District Court to grant the stay and would leave and so forth and this Court granted certiorari.","start":271.248,"stop":279.839,"duration":8.59},{"text":"So we had a situation there where there was an application for a stay under Section 3, the court felt like that Section 4 would go to be enforced in New York that it couldn't grant.","start":279.839,"stop":289.624,"duration":9.79},{"text":"Now, in dealing with relation with that question and relationship between Sections 3 relating to stay and Section 4 relating to enforcement, this Court says, “The plaintiff contends that the District Court was without power to grant the stay because the contract provides that arbitration can be compelled only by proceedings in a State Court of New York.”","start":289.624,"stop":314.752,"duration":25.13},{"text":"The provision here is that, “Either party may apply to the Supreme Court of the State of New York for an order compelling specific performance of this arbitration agreement in accordance with the arbitration law of the State of New York.”","start":314.752,"stop":328.956,"duration":14.2},{"text":"The contract does not in terms prohibit proceedings in the federal court whether it should be construed so as to exclude the bringing of a suit in the federal court to compel specific performance of the agreement arbitrary.","start":328.956,"stop":341.978,"duration":13.02},{"text":"We have no occasion to decide for the District Court was not asked this in the proceeding now under review to compel specific performance.","start":341.978,"stop":351.179,"duration":9.2},{"text":"The motion was to stay the action until arbitration shall have been had and the direction of the Court of Appeals was limited to granting a stay.","start":351.179,"stop":360.044,"duration":8.87},{"text":"Now, if it please the Court, we've come to what this -- this Court said about relationship between Sections 3 and 4.","start":360.044,"stop":367.352,"duration":7.31},{"text":"Section 3 of the United States Arbitration Act provides the broadly that the Court may, “Stay the trial of the action until such arbitration had been had in accordance with the terms of the agreement.”","start":367.352,"stop":381.298,"duration":13.95},{"text":"We think the Court of Appeals was clearly right in concluding that there is no reason to imply that power to grant a stay is conditioned upon the existence of power to compel arbitration in accordance with Section 4 of the Act.","start":381.298,"stop":398.519,"duration":17.22},{"text":"Marine Transit versus Dreyfus if not to the contrary, there is on the other hand strong reason for construing the clause as permitting the federal court to order a stay even when it cannot compel the arbitration.","start":398.519,"stop":413.34,"duration":14.82},{"text":"But otherwise, despite congressional approval of arbitration, it would be impossible to secure a stay of an action in the federal courts when the arbitration agreement provides for compulsory proceedings exclusively in the state court.","start":413.34,"stop":427.798,"duration":14.46},{"text":"So it seems to me, like what the court is saying, if the Court please, is that under Section 3, you can grant a stay which is what is here involved.","start":427.798,"stop":437.832,"duration":10.03},{"text":"Irrespective of whether or not the Court would have jurisdiction to enforce under Section 4, and incidentally in the Circuit Court, Judge Learned Hand in the same case before it got here, made this remark which was confirmed by what I've just read and this appears from page 297 of 70 F.2d.","start":437.832,"stop":460.97,"duration":23.14},{"text":"We see no reason for a limited construction, that is of the United States Arbitration Act, and conclude that Section 3 authorizes a stay even though the arbitration must take place beyond the jurisdiction of the court.","start":460.97,"stop":478.177,"duration":17.21},{"text":"So it seems to me that a right to a stay under Section 3 is unrelated to and fully independent of Section 4.","start":478.177,"stop":488.742,"duration":10.56}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what --","start":488.742,"stop":489.134,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":489.134,"stop":498.231,"duration":9.1}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":498.231,"stop":498.654,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":498.654,"stop":521.943,"duration":23.29}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":521.943,"stop":522.379,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":522.379,"stop":576.771,"duration":54.39}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir.","start":576.771,"stop":578.074,"duration":1.3},{"text":"No sir, I agree with you.","start":578.074,"stop":579.522,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":579.522,"stop":606.823,"duration":27.3}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Goldberg, my view of that is that there is no inconsistency here.","start":606.823,"stop":612.318,"duration":5.5},{"text":"The suit here involved is actually pending in the district which the Miller Act prescribes.","start":612.318,"stop":619.05,"duration":6.73}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"In Georgia?","start":619.05,"stop":619.44,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"In Georgia.","start":619.44,"stop":620.915,"duration":1.47},{"text":"Ultimate judgment in my opinion can be entered in that court which fully conforms to and complies with the Miller Act.","start":620.915,"stop":631.015,"duration":10.1},{"text":"At the same time, it reconciles and conforms to Shanferokee code.","start":631.015,"stop":638.088,"duration":7.07},{"text":"My idea about the way the two would be reconciled is this; the suit is brought as the Miller Act provides it shall be brought in a district where part of the work is to be performed.","start":638.088,"stop":649.415,"duration":11.33},{"text":"The agreement provides for arbitration in New York.","start":649.415,"stop":652.912,"duration":3.5},{"text":"Shanferokee says that's perfectly alright.","start":652.912,"stop":656.084,"duration":3.17},{"text":"Consequently, you stay the proceedings in the Middle District of Georgia.","start":656.084,"stop":660.119,"duration":4.04},{"text":"Just as they did in Shanferokee, you send it to New York to be arbitrated.","start":660.119,"stop":664.318,"duration":4.2},{"text":"When this has been arbitrated in New York, you'd come back in the State of Georgia and enter final judgment, and you reconcile everything.","start":664.318,"stop":670.54,"duration":6.22}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":670.54,"stop":684.969,"duration":14.43}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, and that's the entire purpose of the United States Arbitration Act.","start":684.969,"stop":688.095,"duration":3.13}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":688.095,"stop":690.921,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir.","start":690.921,"stop":691.546,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":691.546,"stop":709.172,"duration":17.63}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Justice Goldberg isn't that true of all the arbitrations?","start":709.172,"stop":712.028,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":712.028,"stop":714.303,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"And there's a policy in favor of it and --","start":714.303,"stop":717.117,"duration":2.81}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] Well my problem is this: if there had been [Inaudible] provision, a general provision of the Congress.","start":717.117,"stop":722.436,"duration":5.32},{"text":"I'm talking about [Inaudible]","start":722.436,"stop":752.047,"duration":29.61}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Goldberg I believe -- Mr. Justice Goldberg, I believe, we may have not change the fact just a slight bit.","start":752.047,"stop":758.193,"duration":6.15},{"text":"It has been held in the lower courts albeit that in Miller Act proceeding you can waive venue.","start":758.193,"stop":766.2,"duration":8.01}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"By general provision you can do this?","start":766.2,"stop":768.525,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir.","start":768.525,"stop":768.907,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"By specific?","start":768.907,"stop":770.083,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":770.083,"stop":770.925,"duration":0.84},{"text":"In one instance for example, they held it was automatically waived because the work was to be done in Newfoundland.","start":770.925,"stop":777.822,"duration":6.9},{"text":"And if you had to bring it in a district where the work was being performed and there's no district in Newfoundland obviously, there had to be some other district in which it could be brought.","start":777.822,"stop":786.91,"duration":9.09},{"text":"The main opinion in the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals incidentally cites other instances and the Lower Federal Courts, I'll admit, flatly holding that the venue provisions of the Miller Act can be waived.","start":786.91,"stop":799.809,"duration":12.9},{"text":"Not a word is there said in the Miller Act prohibiting arbitration then you can be waived and incidentally, that is the next point which I wanted to address myself is what is this provision in the Miller Act?","start":799.809,"stop":813.444,"duration":13.63},{"text":"Is it simply a venue provision which can be waived or is it as Mr. Grant says on any group part of a new federal right which prescribes not only the right but the remedy by which is to be invoked.","start":813.444,"stop":828.165,"duration":14.72},{"text":"Now, that is the thrust of his argument and his main argument, I may add.","start":828.165,"stop":833.321,"duration":5.16},{"text":"He says and his contention is relying on this provision in the Miller Act that suit shall be brought here and not elsewhere.","start":833.321,"stop":841.227,"duration":7.91},{"text":"And that it may be prosecuted there to final judgment.","start":841.227,"stop":845.646,"duration":4.42},{"text":"And that that is a mandate first that you can't do it anywhere else, and second that means you cannot arbitrate.","start":845.646,"stop":854.119,"duration":8.47},{"text":"Now I agree with the principle of law which he cites that where Congress creates a new right unknown to the common law and as an integral part of that right, Congress prescribes a remedy.","start":854.119,"stop":867.853,"duration":13.73},{"text":"The right becomes -- the remedy becomes a part of the right and the right can only be enforced in a manner prescribed.","start":867.853,"stop":874.94,"duration":7.09},{"text":"Mr. Grant cites and I agree with those cases, the case of Wilko versus Swan.","start":874.94,"stop":881.382,"duration":6.44},{"text":"In that case, there was a suit under -- for a violation of the marginal of the provisions of the Securities Act.","start":881.382,"stop":889.887,"duration":8.5},{"text":"Now there was no such suit in common law, the Securities Act created the suit.","start":889.887,"stop":895.524,"duration":5.64},{"text":"It not only prescribed a venue provision but it provided for a non-waiver provision.","start":895.524,"stop":901.108,"duration":5.58},{"text":"And I think clearly having -- Congress having provided a new right and having prescribed the venue provision and having gone further and put in a non-waiver provision, you had to follow it as this Court held in the Wilko case and exactly the same way in the Griffith Saving Bank case which Mr. Grant cites.","start":901.108,"stop":920.077,"duration":18.97},{"text":"That was a Fair Labor Standards Act.","start":920.077,"stop":922.549,"duration":2.47},{"text":"There was no such cause of action as the Fair Labor Standards suit at common law.","start":922.549,"stop":927.357,"duration":4.81},{"text":"Congress created the right.","start":927.357,"stop":929.473,"duration":2.12},{"text":"In creating the right, they made as a part of it as an integral part of it a venue statute.","start":929.473,"stop":935.443,"duration":5.97},{"text":"That also contained a non-waiver provision.","start":935.443,"stop":938.68,"duration":3.24},{"text":"Consequently, the remedy became a part of the right itself and had to be enforced exactly as the statute provided.","start":938.68,"stop":946.003,"duration":7.32}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you, suppose the Miller Act was repealed today, could this man bring a suit under -- on a bond which is not required by law bona fide -- invoking the name of the United States to file the suit?","start":946.003,"stop":962.456,"duration":16.45}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Black, I'm confident to say you anticipate that's the bare point I'm making, the Miller Act creates no new right.","start":962.456,"stop":970.4,"duration":7.94}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understood that, that's why I'm saying what -- what does it do when it allows a suit to be filed in the name of the United States and provides that it should be tried at one place and nowhere else?","start":970.4,"stop":985.821,"duration":15.42},{"text":"What does it do?","start":985.821,"stop":987.873,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm getting just a little ahead of our set but since you ask, I will answer it the best I can.","start":987.873,"stop":993.436,"duration":5.56},{"text":"That provision to my mind is simply a venue provision for a right which has existed as long as a subsidy.","start":993.436,"stop":1001.772,"duration":8.34}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the reason for passing it?","start":1001.772,"stop":1003.732,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"The reason for passing it, if the Court please, is that it is a hold over from the old Heard Act.","start":1003.732,"stop":1011.485,"duration":7.75}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But what was the reason for passing it?","start":1011.485,"stop":1013.903,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"The reason for passing the Heard Act of course it was to or not to create a new right in favor of contractor because they had that right ever since they'd been [Inaudible]","start":1013.903,"stop":1023.452,"duration":9.55}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But what was its purpose?","start":1023.452,"stop":1024.53,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Its purpose was to implement that right.","start":1024.53,"stop":1027.173,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Why?","start":1027.173,"stop":1027.656,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"To make it more secure.","start":1027.656,"stop":1029.117,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Make it?","start":1029.117,"stop":1029.78,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"To make more certain that they got their money.","start":1029.78,"stop":1031.825,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That was the whole purpose?","start":1031.825,"stop":1032.904,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"That was the whole purpose but I beg to point this out sir, it created no new right.","start":1032.904,"stop":1039.298,"duration":6.39},{"text":"If this bond and this contract had been made part of the Miller Act, there still could have been a suit on it.","start":1039.298,"stop":1045.882,"duration":6.58}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"By the United States?","start":1045.882,"stop":1047.104,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1047.104,"stop":1047.868,"duration":0.76},{"text":"There still could have been a suit on it by this plaintiff, this subcontract.","start":1047.868,"stop":1051.525,"duration":3.66},{"text":"It's nothing more than a contract, neither the bond nor the subcontract.","start":1051.525,"stop":1055.443,"duration":3.92}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Could he -- would he have been guaranteed a right to sue at the place where the work was done or would he have been compelled to go where he could get service somewhere on the other man?","start":1055.443,"stop":1064.707,"duration":9.26}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"If it please the Court, isn't it true that every venue statute guarantee you a right to sue in a certain place.","start":1064.707,"stop":1071.94,"duration":7.23},{"text":"And if you can waive --","start":1071.94,"stop":1072.391,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But let's talk about this venue statute in this Act, what was it passed for, except to protect the workers and the materialmen?","start":1072.391,"stop":1080.187,"duration":7.8}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor it was not --","start":1080.187,"stop":1080.768,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"To give a greater security and the government to get its money.","start":1080.768,"stop":1083.229,"duration":2.46}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1083.229,"stop":1083.932,"duration":0.7},{"text":"It was passed for that purpose.","start":1083.932,"stop":1085.947,"duration":2.01},{"text":"Now, as to the venue provision, however if the Court please, the legislative history does not indicate entirely that that was the purpose of it.","start":1085.947,"stop":1096.029,"duration":10.08},{"text":"If I may trace the history of the Miller, I mean of the Heard Act from which this provision was derived, Your Honor will recall that the Heard Act provided for one suit for everybody to be brought by the government in which contractors and subcontractors could intervene and if there was anything left after the government got its money, they could adjudicate their claims to final judgment.","start":1096.029,"stop":1122.258,"duration":26.23},{"text":"And since there was to be but one suit on behalf of everybody, of course, there had to be someplace specified where was it to be brought and therefore, the Heard Act first contained this language that it should be brought in a district where part of the work was performed and that it should be -- could -- could be prosecuted to final judgment right.","start":1122.258,"stop":1144.598,"duration":22.34},{"text":"Now, that provision would have been unnecessary when the Miller Act was passed because the Miller Act came along and instead of creating one bond for everybody as the Heard Act had done, it created two bonds; one for the performance bond for the government and one of payment bond for contractors.","start":1144.598,"stop":1164.866,"duration":20.27},{"text":"So really, there was no need, you might say, to any longer have this provision about bringing the suit in that place and for prosecution at the final judgment.","start":1164.866,"stop":1175.408,"duration":10.54}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think Congress has left to that without it meaning anything?","start":1175.408,"stop":1178.212,"duration":2.8}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1178.212,"stop":1179.418,"duration":1.21},{"text":"The congressional hearing recite that the bonding companies wanted it preserved because, otherwise, they would be subject to numerous suits in various districts which might ultimately exceed the amounts of their bond limits, and according to the hearings, and the congressional hearings, it was the bondsman, not the contractors, not the subcontractors, but the bondsman who asked that this venue provision be kept in that.","start":1179.418,"stop":1212.968,"duration":33.55},{"text":"So, I submit that it is nothing more than a venue statute; that Miller Act is just like any other act; that just like any other venues section it can be waived; and that where the parties have agreed to arbitration as they have in this case, it has been waived.","start":1212.968,"stop":1232.648,"duration":19.68},{"text":"Now --","start":1232.648,"stop":1233.638,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1233.638,"stop":1242.861,"duration":9.22}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"To an existing suit.","start":1242.861,"stop":1244.227,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1244.227,"stop":1244.845,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I think this Court had recognized that distinction many times.","start":1244.845,"stop":1252.117,"duration":7.27},{"text":"I don't see that there's anything wrong with waiving in advance if the waiver concerns a right going out of the contract.","start":1252.117,"stop":1262.416,"duration":10.3},{"text":"Now, if it was a right that arose in some other way, obviously an agreement in advance to waive venue in a tort case might be one thing.","start":1262.416,"stop":1271.578,"duration":9.16},{"text":"If it were an action brought by statute, but it -- right in this case arises it out of a contract which the parties made with each other, and that there's some -- certainly an area in which they had the right to contract.","start":1271.578,"stop":1285.998,"duration":14.42},{"text":"And where the waiver is contained in a contract giving rise to the cause of action, I have seen nothing in the decisions of this Court which would indicate that it could not be waived in advance.","start":1285.998,"stop":1298.879,"duration":12.88}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, [Inaudible] to the extent of the -- that arbitration agreement were enforceable law at all waiver is [Inaudible]","start":1298.879,"stop":1309.148,"duration":10.27}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":1309.148,"stop":1310.096,"duration":0.95},{"text":"Yes sir, or otherwise that could be no arbitration agreement.","start":1310.096,"stop":1313.621,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And that result in -- probably that you would enforce that you've waived the jury trial, is it?","start":1313.621,"stop":1319.037,"duration":5.42}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1319.037,"stop":1320.415,"duration":1.38},{"text":"Incidentally, the only arbitration agreements that this Court had ever turned over that I know of, the only arbitration statutes that have ever overturned, our arbitration statute which makes arbitration compulsory that is where they say, this must be arbitrated and they legislate you out of court.","start":1320.415,"stop":1337.756,"duration":17.34},{"text":"Now, in state in the Kansas City Packinghouse case that this Court held you couldn't do that and in several cases following, but as far as I know and dealing with State Arbitration Act long before the Miller Act and the old United States Arbitration Act came up, this Court have never overturned an Arbitration Act where there was an agreement for arbitration.","start":1337.756,"stop":1358.463,"duration":20.71},{"text":"The only place they've overturned them is where the statute says, “You can't litigate, you must arbitrate.”","start":1358.463,"stop":1364.417,"duration":5.95}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Edenfield, I take it, your argument is then mainly prerequisite whether arbitration is available at all rather than to where it must take place?","start":1364.417,"stop":1376.466,"duration":12.05},{"text":"And --","start":1376.466,"stop":1376.646,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor this may sound -- I've, I hope I'm not --","start":1376.646,"stop":1380.145,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"It seems to me that -- it seems to me that before you get through, you ought to cover the -- Justice Black's point on Section -- Section 4 in Arbitration Act.","start":1380.145,"stop":1392.858,"duration":12.71},{"text":"The -- it seems to me that the court that did have jurisdiction as the Georgia Court and if you refuse to arbitrate anywhere other than in New York, or if you refuse, say you refused to arbitrate at all --","start":1392.858,"stop":1412.053,"duration":19.2}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1412.053,"stop":1412.846,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the subcontractor wants his money and you say, no, you refuse to arbitrate at all.","start":1412.846,"stop":1417.146,"duration":4.3},{"text":"If the subcontractor goes into the Georgia Court under the Arbitration Act and gets an order to arbitrate --","start":1417.146,"stop":1423.017,"duration":5.87}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1423.017,"stop":1424.404,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, the arbitration in that instance must take place in Georgia under Section 4.","start":1424.404,"stop":1431.308,"duration":6.9}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I, I don't read it that way.","start":1431.308,"stop":1434.499,"duration":3.19},{"text":"Now, if -- if -- if --","start":1434.499,"stop":1435.892,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I just --","start":1435.892,"stop":1436.565,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"I may be allowed to reply.","start":1436.565,"stop":1438.337,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't mean to interrupt your --","start":1438.337,"stop":1440.441,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, I'm glad --","start":1440.441,"stop":1440.751,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- your argument but --","start":1440.751,"stop":1441.552,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm glad you brought it up, but I think that is clearly answered in Shanferokee.","start":1441.552,"stop":1445.92,"duration":4.37}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it is not.","start":1445.92,"stop":1446.907,"duration":0.99},{"text":"Shan -- I -- I think that Shanferokee simply says that you may have a -- you may have a stay and the --","start":1446.907,"stop":1458.764,"duration":11.86}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir and that's all is before this Court.","start":1458.764,"stop":1460.564,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And it -- well, I'm not so sure about that because you're wanting to say, and the -- the net result of your stay is that you will not arbitrate anywhere but in New York.","start":1460.564,"stop":1470.848,"duration":10.28}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, let me state here and now --","start":1470.848,"stop":1472.089,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You are in effect using the judicial proceedings to enforce arbitration in New York from the Arbitration Act says that the arbitration and that if -- if you are to be compelled to arbitrate, it must take place within the district of the court that ordered the arbitration.","start":1472.089,"stop":1487.433,"duration":15.34}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, as I -- that -- I may be in error about my memory of Section 4, but as I understood Section 4 it says, a party aggrieved by the refusal of the opposite party to arbitrate.","start":1487.433,"stop":1498.644,"duration":11.21}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":1498.644,"stop":1499.814,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1499.814,"stop":1500.103,"duration":0.29},{"text":"Now, he's aggrieved by it --","start":1500.103,"stop":1501.266,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And he's aggrieved by your refusing to arbitrate anywhere but in New York.","start":1501.266,"stop":1504.465,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1504.465,"stop":1504.856,"duration":0.39},{"text":"It's the other way around, we aggrieved by his refusal, we're trying to get on it.","start":1504.856,"stop":1508.362,"duration":3.51}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I said -- that he's aggrieved by your refusal to arbitrate anywhere but in New York.","start":1508.362,"stop":1517.143,"duration":8.78},{"text":"Now, if he could go to -- let's assume now he goes into the suit that he has now brought in Georgia.","start":1517.143,"stop":1522.368,"duration":5.22}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1522.368,"stop":1523.647,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And asked that court to order you to arbitrate in Georgia.","start":1523.647,"stop":1528.338,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me say this, we won't to object to it.","start":1528.338,"stop":1530.679,"duration":2.34},{"text":"I don't interpret the Act as permitting it or Shanferokee as requiring, but if that's the ultimate outcome of it, Your Honor, we have no objection to arbitrate in Georgia if we can find a way to do it under this Act but I don't read the Act or the decision in that manner.","start":1530.679,"stop":1544.811,"duration":14.13}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But that's what the court required you to do, the Court of Appeals.","start":1544.811,"stop":1548.539,"duration":3.73},{"text":"Court of Appeals' opinion, if you follow it, requires that this arbitration take place in New York, orders these people to stop and pay, the District Court sustained, they've got to go to New York and arbitrate under the Court of Appeals opinion, haven't they?","start":1548.539,"stop":1566.273,"duration":17.73},{"text":"I may have misread it, but that's the way I read it.","start":1566.273,"stop":1568.767,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Black, I agree with you and I think that's what the -- not only what the Court of Appeals have in my opinion is what is right.","start":1568.767,"stop":1575.713,"duration":6.95}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that.","start":1575.713,"stop":1579.091,"duration":3.38},{"text":"I understand that, but that certainly what it has.","start":1579.091,"stop":1581.864,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But if they were to amend Mr. Edenfield, if they would have tomorrow to amend in District Court in Georgia.","start":1581.864,"stop":1589.321,"duration":7.46},{"text":"Now I'm saying they want an order of arbitration.","start":1589.321,"stop":1591.894,"duration":2.57}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"In Georgia.","start":1591.894,"stop":1592.698,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, in Georgia.","start":1592.698,"stop":1594.245,"duration":1.55},{"text":"This sentence in Section 4, would certainly on the face of it, seems to indicate that that's the only order of the District Court could give because it reads the hearing and proceedings under subsequently shall be within the district in which the petition for an order directing such arbitration is filed, doesn't it?","start":1594.245,"stop":1616.92,"duration":22.68}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean the order of enforcement matter?","start":1616.92,"stop":1618.639,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1618.639,"stop":1619.477,"duration":0.84},{"text":"I'm suggesting that if they were to amend in this -- their pleadings in the District Court and ask an order directing you to arbitrate under the agreement.","start":1619.477,"stop":1629.048,"duration":9.57},{"text":"Wouldn't the order have to direct the proceedings an arbitration to be held in the district in Georgia?","start":1629.048,"stop":1636.663,"duration":7.62}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't understand that it would, if the Court please, under Shanferokee.","start":1636.663,"stop":1640.752,"duration":4.09}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Shanferokee involved a stay.","start":1640.752,"stop":1643.086,"duration":2.33},{"text":"Now, what you're saying is the policy as to the location of arbitration is different under Section 3 than it is under Section 4 and if you just get a stay, the court stays this action that you felt would agree to arbitrate.","start":1643.086,"stop":1660.283,"duration":17.2},{"text":"Now, you go ahead and arbitrate, where is that going to go into this lawsuit until you've arbitrated.","start":1660.283,"stop":1665.545,"duration":5.26},{"text":"Then -- but it does order arbitration, you're saying then that the arbitration may and must take place where the agreement says it should take place.","start":1665.545,"stop":1677.687,"duration":12.14}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that's permissible.","start":1677.687,"stop":1679.777,"duration":2.09},{"text":"I think that's what the Circuit Court opinion suggests and I think that the law --","start":1679.777,"stop":1683.073,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I understand that, I understand what the Circuit Court said, but Section 4 said that if you have the -- that if there's an order to arbitrate, an order specifically enforcing an agreement to arbitrate, the arbitration must take place in that district.","start":1683.073,"stop":1698.207,"duration":15.13},{"text":"That's what Section 4 says [Inaudible]","start":1698.207,"stop":1702.13,"duration":3.92}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1702.13,"stop":1702.275,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Maybe it's better than [Inaudible] but it has mentioned that.","start":1702.275,"stop":1706.929,"duration":4.65}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Sir.","start":1706.929,"stop":1707.317,"duration":0.39},{"text":"I don't think it had. I think the only case dealing with 3 and 4 is Shanferokee.","start":1707.317,"stop":1711.806,"duration":4.49},{"text":"But in Shanferokee, they did order in a federal court to arbitrate in state court.","start":1711.806,"stop":1718.507,"duration":6.7}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't read it that way, frankly Mr. Edenfield --","start":1718.507,"stop":1722.831,"duration":4.32}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm reading from the --","start":1722.831,"stop":1723.801,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought all that they did in Shanferokee was to say that whether or not an order of arbitration could be entered under Section 4 a stay could be granted under Section 3.","start":1723.801,"stop":1737.216,"duration":13.41}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Brennan, I overstated my position.","start":1737.216,"stop":1739.71,"duration":2.49},{"text":"Let me go back and read what the Circuit Court said again and it didn't actually order that, but it certainly is broad enough in scope to encompass it.","start":1739.71,"stop":1747.73,"duration":8.02},{"text":"We see no reason for a limited construction of the Arbitration Act and conclude that Section 3 authorizes the stay even though the arbitration must take place beyond the jurisdiction of the court.","start":1747.73,"stop":1761.36,"duration":13.63},{"text":"Now, that to my -- and that's what this Court affirmed.","start":1761.36,"stop":1763.892,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you if this -- you're asking for an interpretation of the Arbitration Act in this, are you not?","start":1763.892,"stop":1769.894,"duration":6}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1769.894,"stop":1770.191,"duration":0.3},{"text":"I think it involves interpretation for --","start":1770.191,"stop":1772.442,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And you're saying we would have to hold the Congress, hold that 435 members of Congress on the different states in the union and the Senate passed a bill intending that the man in the South Georgia could waive his right, to have his case tried under the Miller Act in South Georgia but must go all the way to New York or to London as you said where some of the cases available --","start":1772.442,"stop":1801.241,"duration":28.8}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1801.241,"stop":1801.8,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Or to Switzerland, I think of them went to Switzerland if I'm not mistaken, that Congress passed an act which we must construe to meaning that under Arbitration Act, a man in South Georgia can waive his right so that he has to go all the way to Switzerland, or New York City and hire lawyers of New York who are familiar with New York proceeding, the New York law in order to try his case as a subcontractor from South Georgia.","start":1801.8,"stop":1830.692,"duration":28.89}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Black, those 435 Congressmen not only passed that in 1925, they reenacted it in 1947 verbatim.","start":1830.692,"stop":1838.43,"duration":7.74}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But did anybody say at that time or can you find anything in the record that indicates they were saying if that constituent far removed from New York City will make a subcontract, would have to go all the way to New York City and try cases in a -- on a foreign language to them so far as arbitration is concerned?","start":1838.43,"stop":1859.976,"duration":21.55}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice, if I may say --","start":1859.976,"stop":1860.751,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It might be good for New York lawyers but I have an idea all of them when I understood it merely have a New York lawyer.","start":1860.751,"stop":1866.972,"duration":6.22}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"If I may say so this argument of inconvenience doesn't impresses me, for this reason: that's true every time you have interstate commerce.","start":1866.972,"stop":1874.94,"duration":7.97},{"text":"One man lives in California and the other one is live in Maryland.","start":1874.94,"stop":1877.696,"duration":2.76},{"text":"They've got to litigate one place to the other one, one have to get to cross the country.","start":1877.696,"stop":1881.114,"duration":3.42}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But this Court and the Congress, they are moving further and further towards the idea doing a way with inconvenient forum, then their cases be tried where they can't have a right, and where the part is up there with their witnesses.","start":1881.114,"stop":1896.664,"duration":15.55}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, it may be just as inconvenient for us to go to Macon.","start":1896.664,"stop":1900.116,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, where did this transaction take place?","start":1900.116,"stop":1903.52,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"It was a New York contract.","start":1903.52,"stop":1905.573,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What?","start":1905.573,"stop":1905.997,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"It was a New York contract.","start":1905.997,"stop":1907.924,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you mean this bad rule they say didn't have any people to do it work.","start":1907.924,"stop":1914.884,"duration":6.96},{"text":"You got a contract in New York and made a contract which he said was to be governed by the laws of New York, but where was the work performed?","start":1914.884,"stop":1921.117,"duration":6.23}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"The work was performed in Georgia.","start":1921.117,"stop":1922.651,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"By a Georgia contractor?","start":1922.651,"stop":1924.122,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1924.122,"stop":1924.38,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1924.38,"stop":1925.01,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Among others from other state.","start":1925.01,"stop":1926.649,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, a Georgia, Cumming contractor.","start":1926.649,"stop":1929.015,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1929.015,"stop":1930.119,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And why would the witnesses for the transaction has appeared down there most likely live?","start":1930.119,"stop":1936.266,"duration":6.15}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course, they'd most likely live in Georgia, if the Court please.","start":1936.266,"stop":1938.698,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And they would have (Voice Overlap) their deposition.","start":1938.698,"stop":1941.67,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"That is not necessarily true.","start":1941.67,"stop":1943.216,"duration":1.55},{"text":"Suppose -- and they were subcontractors from other states, suppose a subcontractor was right across the street in New York from the main contract then the inconvenience would be on the other --","start":1943.216,"stop":1953.385,"duration":10.17}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Where would the witnesses still be?","start":1953.385,"stop":1955.999,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"They probably would be in New York because the supervisor personnel came from New York.","start":1955.999,"stop":1961.482,"duration":5.48},{"text":"So the record show other subcontractors came from other states and I would assume they would be with --","start":1961.482,"stop":1968.209,"duration":6.73}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the issue is raised by this man [Inaudible] for evidence of fraud to the other.","start":1968.209,"stop":1973.752,"duration":5.54},{"text":"Allege that while he was there, certain things took place and didn't pay him and so forth, where would those witnesses most likely be?","start":1973.752,"stop":1980.317,"duration":6.57}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let us assume for the sake of argument, Your Honor, that they come from Georgia, but the man signed a contract.","start":1980.317,"stop":1986.059,"duration":5.74},{"text":"He had a lawyer when he signed it, so Mr. Grant said yesterday, he apparently read it.","start":1986.059,"stop":1992.21,"duration":6.15},{"text":"He apparently understood it.","start":1992.21,"stop":1993.573,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That was formally a contract prevalent in various parts of the country by which people who borrowed $10 or $ 40 or a $100 from a loan man on high rates of interest would agree to the lender to accept service for the immanent court where they will not present, confess judgment both for the interest in appeal and as I recall it some of those contracts have been held not to be good.","start":1993.573,"stop":2022.004,"duration":28.43}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2022.004,"stop":2022.488,"duration":0.48},{"text":"You understand, I display many connection with it Your Honor.","start":2022.488,"stop":2026.101,"duration":3.61},{"text":"[Laughter]","start":2026.101,"stop":2027.87,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Edenfield, it seems to me that one response to the Section 4 argument is that there maybe other ways to have arbitration enforced and that the Arbitration Act would be exclusive vehicle for enforcing arbitration.","start":2027.87,"stop":2047.261,"duration":19.39}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice White, I think I'm being forced to a position that I don't need to go to.","start":2047.261,"stop":2052.389,"duration":5.13},{"text":"If -- if it be the law that the arbitration must take place in Georgia, so be it.","start":2052.389,"stop":2058.101,"duration":5.71},{"text":"That's alright with us, but I was asked the question what I thought about it and I said so.","start":2058.101,"stop":2064.126,"duration":6.03},{"text":"I'm frankly willing to go to Georgia to arbitrate.","start":2064.126,"stop":2066.931,"duration":2.8}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think we do need to talk about this.","start":2066.931,"stop":2070.563,"duration":3.63},{"text":"I mean, I think it's very important point.","start":2070.563,"stop":2072.283,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2072.283,"stop":2117.431,"duration":45.15}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"That had nothing to do with the appealability of the order, Your Honor.","start":2117.431,"stop":2120.085,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2120.085,"stop":2174.402,"duration":54.32}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I think you got to the section.","start":2174.402,"stop":2176.405,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2176.405,"stop":2194.152,"duration":17.75}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor I --","start":2194.152,"stop":2194.615,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2194.615,"stop":2220.432,"duration":25.82}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"I did not read Section 4 as requiring the arbitration in that district.","start":2220.432,"stop":2226.039,"duration":5.61},{"text":"I thought that was referring to a hearing about whether or not there was a valid arbitration agreement.","start":2226.039,"stop":2231.948,"duration":5.91}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Assuming there was [Inaudible]","start":2231.948,"stop":2269.963,"duration":38.02}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, let me say this, I think you did move one step further than Shanferokee go, but I think that’s definitely inevitable.","start":2269.963,"stop":2278.753,"duration":8.79},{"text":"I mean to that extent, I agree.","start":2278.753,"stop":2280.581,"duration":1.83},{"text":"Now, it says, if what is says that we don’t have to decide that because you just deal with a stay.","start":2280.581,"stop":2285.157,"duration":4.58},{"text":"But I think it’s implicit in what they say that when he refuses to arbitrate when after the stay, obviously they are setting status quo forever and the next move is going to be to enforce it.","start":2285.157,"stop":2297.559,"duration":12.4},{"text":"And my own understanding of 4 is that this move to enforce can be made in Georgia and frankly reading 4 and Shanferokee together, I thought it could be held in New York but if it can't, so be it.","start":2297.559,"stop":2310.836,"duration":13.28}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But would that settle it?","start":2310.836,"stop":2312.908,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":2312.908,"stop":2313.603,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Would that settle it?","start":2313.603,"stop":2316.36,"duration":2.76},{"text":"They allege that your contract to arbitrate is no good under the Arbitration Act for one reason because you have provided for an arbitration at a place where the act forbids it.","start":2316.36,"stop":2327.171,"duration":10.81}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court please, we have provided for arbitration in several ways and the arbitration provision goes on and says, if we can’t arbitrate under New York Civil Practice Act, it should be arbitrated under the provision of the American Arbitration Association.","start":2327.171,"stop":2341.565,"duration":14.39},{"text":"Now admittedly that says, it shall be in New York.","start":2341.565,"stop":2345.292,"duration":3.73}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You have an agreement to arbitrate in New York and nowhere else, isn't that right?","start":2345.292,"stop":2351.227,"duration":5.93}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir and let me say this, Mr. Justice Black.","start":2351.227,"stop":2355.822,"duration":4.6},{"text":"I don't see how they could let that man to arbitrate in Shanferokee and cut me out of it when I have an agreement just like his.","start":2355.822,"stop":2366.098,"duration":10.28},{"text":"I think the way I would construe would harmonize --","start":2366.098,"stop":2368.928,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It might not do your irreparable damages.","start":2368.928,"stop":2371.675,"duration":2.75},{"text":"The court is still open in Georgia, including the federal court.","start":2371.675,"stop":2376.213,"duration":4.54}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2376.213,"stop":2376.711,"duration":0.5},{"text":"We're aware of that Your Honor, but these people did agree in a contract that they would arbitrate in New York just -- and they did it in Shanferokee and they stated until they did it.","start":2376.711,"stop":2392.278,"duration":15.57},{"text":"Now, what happened thereafter, we don't know.","start":2392.278,"stop":2395.169,"duration":2.89},{"text":"And I would say one thing, if the interpretation of Mr. Grant and I'm trying to get back now to where I was awhile ago, if the interpretation argued by Mr. Grant is sustained, the effect of it will be, if the Court please, to imply the repeal to the Arbitration Act to the extent of Miller Act cases.","start":2395.169,"stop":2414.18,"duration":19.01},{"text":"In fact, that itself is what Mr. Grant argues in his brief.","start":2414.18,"stop":2418.33,"duration":4.15},{"text":"He said that arbitration act was passed first, now the Miller Act was passed second with these unusual provisions about why you bring a suit and prosecute under final judgment.","start":2418.33,"stop":2429.524,"duration":11.19},{"text":"And to that extent, the Arbitration Act, you go then to say to a repeal pro tanto, but in substance, he said that, that takes the Miller Act cases out of it.","start":2429.524,"stop":2438.418,"duration":8.89},{"text":"Well, of course, that argument in the first place implied repeals are not favored.","start":2438.418,"stop":2443.908,"duration":5.49},{"text":"If my theory is correct, they can be harmonized.","start":2443.908,"stop":2447.531,"duration":3.62},{"text":"And furthermore, while it's true that the Arbitration Act was passed before the Miller Act, and therefore, there might be an implied repeal by the later Act, the Arbitration Act was subsequently enacted as substantive law in 1947, 12 years after the passage of the Miller Act and not a syllable in it was changed.","start":2447.531,"stop":2470.748,"duration":23.22},{"text":"So, Congress had not only said that that was their policy as far as the Arbitration Act is concerned, they've never said there was any exception in Miller Act cases, and after the Miller Act, they have repeated it in exactly the same language.","start":2470.748,"stop":2485.328,"duration":14.58},{"text":"So that I say that what he is seeking to do, would be to work an implied repeal and that in spite of the fact that Congress had reenacted.","start":2485.328,"stop":2493.47,"duration":8.14},{"text":"Now, if the Court please, I don't know what my time is but I want to move on to this business of fraud just a minute, if I may, which was argued by Mr. Grant.","start":2493.47,"stop":2502.639,"duration":9.17},{"text":"I am sure the Court would be aware, how easy it would be to destroy any policy of arbitration.","start":2502.639,"stop":2511.269,"duration":8.63},{"text":"If it could be furthered the way in every case by having the unwilling party come forward and say it was obtained by deceptive fraud, however ground this or however frivolous.","start":2511.269,"stop":2524.228,"duration":12.96}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the defense, however, is it not?","start":2524.228,"stop":2526.911,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2526.911,"stop":2527.271,"duration":0.36},{"text":"I don't think so, Your Honor.","start":2527.271,"stop":2528.452,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you --","start":2528.452,"stop":2528.602,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"It would be a defense to the merit -- yes, sir, but not to arbitration.","start":2528.602,"stop":2532.561,"duration":3.96}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Not a defense to this arbitration agreement if you can prove that it was abuse of law?","start":2532.561,"stop":2540.071,"duration":7.51}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- of course, it would to that -- in that way, Your Honor, but I'm saying that just the allegation of fraud would not prevent arbitration.","start":2540.071,"stop":2547.72,"duration":7.65},{"text":"Now, let's --","start":2547.72,"stop":2547.941,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not an allegation but maybe if an allegation of fraud was made and they were denied the right to prove it, that would change the situation.","start":2547.941,"stop":2556.464,"duration":8.52}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now either this question so far as I know had not been discussed by this Court.","start":2556.464,"stop":2562.62,"duration":6.16},{"text":"But there was a very interesting case, Devonshire Fabrics which is cited in our brief, where that question did come up and was considered by Judge Medina in New York and incidentally, this Court granted certiorari and as our judge, the case must have been settled because it never, I mean, it was declared moot or something or so.","start":2562.62,"stop":2584.703,"duration":22.08},{"text":"But in any rate, in that case, Judge Medina flatly holds that in order to -- for fraud to prevent arbitration, the arbitration provision must itself have been obtained by fraud.","start":2584.703,"stop":2600.911,"duration":16.21},{"text":"Now, in this case, the only allegation of fraud in the whole petition, as far as that's concerned, is something that was written into the contract and which he presumably read before he signed.","start":2600.911,"stop":2614.425,"duration":13.51},{"text":"And the only allegation which concerns in any manner whether the arbitration agreement excerpt was procured by fraud was a statement that it was maliciously inserted in the contract.","start":2614.425,"stop":2625.598,"duration":11.17}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Didn't he say as a part of the scheme --","start":2625.598,"stop":2628.445,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2628.445,"stop":2628.62,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of fraud to subcontractors and that this was to be a device used in order to do that?","start":2628.62,"stop":2634.489,"duration":5.87}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2634.489,"stop":2634.932,"duration":0.44},{"text":"Your Honor, that's what it said.","start":2634.932,"stop":2636.519,"duration":1.59},{"text":"Now, --","start":2636.519,"stop":2636.743,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose -- suppose he could prove that, is it your argument that that wouldn't be a defense to the arbitration – wouldn't able him to say, I don't have to arbitrate?","start":2636.743,"stop":2649.158,"duration":12.41}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, that I could write something in a contract and by putting it in there so the man can read it, defraud him is a little bit part of --","start":2649.158,"stop":2658.105,"duration":8.95}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The books are filled with cases that people have been defrauded by written contracts.","start":2658.105,"stop":2663.126,"duration":5.02}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2663.126,"stop":2664.108,"duration":0.98},{"text":"But that doesn't mean that -- just because he puts something in there that was a fraud.","start":2664.108,"stop":2668.917,"duration":4.81}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, but that's not what he alleges.","start":2668.917,"stop":2671.379,"duration":2.46},{"text":"He alleges that he put it in there as a part of a scheme and plan to defeat his rights and to defeat other subcontractors' rights and that the device he was using was to -- and use them to sign this arbitration agreement provision.","start":2671.379,"stop":2688.885,"duration":17.51}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please Court, I understand the Justice's position but let me -- I don't agree with that that that's what Devonshire hold.","start":2688.885,"stop":2696.489,"duration":7.6}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not talking about what Devonshire hold.","start":2696.489,"stop":2698.343,"duration":1.85},{"text":"I'm talking about --","start":2698.343,"stop":2698.596,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't – I don't agree that that's the law of this case on this allegation but may I proceed to another reason why that --","start":2698.596,"stop":2704.437,"duration":5.84}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, all I'm talking about, are you saying that the allegations are not sufficient or that it is not a defense to an arbitration agreement to show that was induced by fraud?","start":2704.437,"stop":2714.456,"duration":10.02}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"I am saying that the allegations are not sufficient and I am further saying that even if they were sufficient to draw it into fraud, he waived them by continuing to perform after he found out what was going on.","start":2714.456,"stop":2729.649,"duration":15.19}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that the law of Georgia by the contract?","start":2729.649,"stop":2730.983,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"It is the law of as far as I know of every jurisdiction that where a man has a contract --","start":2730.983,"stop":2734.711,"duration":3.73}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"This could be governed by the law of Georgia, wouldn't it?","start":2734.711,"stop":2738.333,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"I have some doubt about it.","start":2738.333,"stop":2739.825,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"So far as the fraud is concerned?","start":2739.825,"stop":2742.641,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it probably would but that's the law of Georgia.","start":2742.641,"stop":2746.213,"duration":3.57}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not so sure of that from the cases I read on it.","start":2746.213,"stop":2751.236,"duration":5.02}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, we have cited some in our brief but that the law as I understand it is that if a man claims that a contract is shot through with the fraud and he wants to resend it --","start":2751.236,"stop":2763.657,"duration":12.42}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what he claims?","start":2763.657,"stop":2764.374,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"-- as soon as he learned of the fraud, he must stop.","start":2764.374,"stop":2769.132,"duration":4.76},{"text":"He has an election of remedies, whether to treat the contract as continuing or whether to stop and claim fraud.","start":2769.132,"stop":2776.937,"duration":7.8},{"text":"Now, by his own allegation, he went ahead and completely performed he says, “everyone of these things and the allegations of fraud he makes where allegations involving things that he must have known about before he completed, and some of them from the very inception of the contact.”","start":2776.937,"stop":2797.279,"duration":20.34},{"text":"I say and --","start":2797.279,"stop":2798.052,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) the Court of Appeals went on?","start":2798.052,"stop":2800.941,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"The Court of Appeals did not really get in to that if the Court please, but I simply say that the Court --","start":2800.941,"stop":2808.336,"duration":7.39}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The District Court held that was sufficient, didn't it?","start":2808.336,"stop":2812.213,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2812.213,"stop":2812.887,"duration":0.67},{"text":"Yes sir, I believe it did, but the Circuit Court as I recall it did not --","start":2812.887,"stop":2818.362,"duration":5.47}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But he had Georgia judge?","start":2818.362,"stop":2821.002,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"The Circuit Judge Tuttle, yes sir.","start":2821.002,"stop":2823.93,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean the district judge.","start":2823.93,"stop":2825.925,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"So does Judge Tuttle of the Circuit.","start":2825.925,"stop":2828.409,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But Judge Tuttle you say did not go into it.","start":2828.409,"stop":2832.112,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"He mentioned it but I -- I declare.","start":2832.112,"stop":2836.045,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Has he?","start":2836.045,"stop":2836.661,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"That wasn't a controlling issue in the case to Judge Tuttle.","start":2836.661,"stop":2840.332,"duration":3.67},{"text":"I say to the Court in all sincerity that I believe upon and in spite of the liberal rules of civil procedures that a reading of these allegations of fraud will, to my mind, demonstrate that they border on being frivolous.","start":2840.332,"stop":2856.663,"duration":16.33},{"text":"I also say that he waived any claim of fraud, when he continued with the job after he knew of its existence.","start":2856.663,"stop":2865.235,"duration":8.57},{"text":"And that's quite apart from the contingence in Devonshire that he must have alleged that that was induced by fraud and I think to my mind that means more than saying somebody fraudulently inserted it even for the purposes of defraud.","start":2865.235,"stop":2879.104,"duration":13.87},{"text":"Thank you.","start":2879.104,"stop":2879.667,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's assume he -- assuming that he didn't waive his claim of fraud and assuming that there was fraud in this contract not specifically in regard to the arbitration, as you say it requires [Inaudible] you would say arbitration must go forward even though there is the fraud claim in the picture.","start":2879.667,"stop":2903.59,"duration":23.92}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2903.59,"stop":2904.184,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Now to carry that on through, what happens in the arbitration you're seeking?","start":2904.184,"stop":2910.268,"duration":6.08}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":2910.268,"stop":2911.221,"duration":0.95},{"text":"As I read Devonshire, they would try to claim a fraud there.","start":2911.221,"stop":2914.549,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And what if it was sustained?","start":2914.549,"stop":2916.695,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Then I think there would be an award accordingly.","start":2916.695,"stop":2921.697,"duration":5}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And that the fraud claimed it be once and for all litigated and decided in a forum by the arbitration.","start":2921.697,"stop":2930.192,"duration":8.49}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that's -- I think that is the gist as I understand the Devonshire Your Honor.","start":2930.192,"stop":2935.768,"duration":5.58},{"text":"Now, this Court has never passed on that question Your Honor posed.","start":2935.768,"stop":2940.519,"duration":4.75},{"text":"I think any other rule, if the Court please, would allow an unwilling party to destroy any arbitration agreement anywhere at anytime by simply alleging fraud whether --","start":2940.519,"stop":2951.357,"duration":10.84}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2951.357,"stop":2955.552,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir but before -- when he proves this before the jury and the arbitration is gone.","start":2955.552,"stop":2960.409,"duration":4.86}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"He has to make some thing [Inaudible] fraud?","start":2960.409,"stop":2964.023,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Well that --","start":2964.023,"stop":2964.296,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2964.296,"stop":2967.163,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Then -- then I'm in fine shape, Your Honor because that's what I say this man hadn't done.","start":2967.163,"stop":2971.313,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I know that's what you say but I assume that [Inaudible] I get your answer that just like any other claim on the contract, the arbitration decides it.","start":2971.313,"stop":2982.354,"duration":11.04}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2982.354,"stop":2984.475,"duration":2.12},{"text":"And I say repeat if that were not true --","start":2984.475,"stop":2985.459,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And that you -- you -- what you're saying is that the agreement to arbitrate not only includes matters arising under the contract, its interpretation and its applicability things like that but it's the – but fraud completely [Inaudible] in contract antecedent thereto --","start":2985.459,"stop":3005.347,"duration":19.89}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"In the procurement thereof.","start":3005.347,"stop":3006.354,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3006.354,"stop":3007.177,"duration":0.82},{"text":"Do you think that the agreement to arbitrate -- that they agree to arbitrate that kind of claim too?","start":3007.177,"stop":3012.567,"duration":5.39}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that's my impression if the Court please, but what I'm saying is however that may be if the Court -- if this Court is to permit a defendant to simply come in and allege fraud and thereby go to a jury and destroy arbitration.","start":3012.567,"stop":3025.894,"duration":13.33}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Hasn't the -- hasn't the Court of Appeals decided that under this contract, this fraud issue is arbitrable?","start":3025.894,"stop":3035.406,"duration":9.51}]},{"speakerName":"Newell Edenfield","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, I judge that's the effect of it because it relies upon Devonshire and cites it.","start":3035.406,"stop":3045.316,"duration":9.91}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Grant.","start":3045.316,"stop":3046.441,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":3046.441,"stop":3050.665,"duration":4.22},{"text":"I would like to make reply to some observations made by Mr. Edenfield and first, I will address myself to his last argument that there was a waiver of the fraud by continuing to perform the contract.","start":3050.665,"stop":3064.298,"duration":13.63},{"text":"It's specifically alleged in the complaint and set out on page 64 of the record, Moseley had no knowledge of the fraudulent and illegal scheme plan and design as herein alleged and is specified in subparagraphs A, B, C, D, E, F and G hereof until after he had completed his performance under the contract and then begin to receive from the defendant contractor a flood of bills for alleged back charges and denials for the first time of plaintiff's claims for compensation for work done by him which was not covered by the term of the contract.","start":3064.298,"stop":3101.345,"duration":37.05}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":3101.345,"stop":3117.273,"duration":15.93}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3117.273,"stop":3117.753,"duration":0.48},{"text":"I definitely argue that, Your Honor.","start":3117.753,"stop":3120.052,"duration":2.3},{"text":"I argue it because we allege that this contract -- in preparing this contract and then entering into it, set out with a fraudulent scheme to obtain money and materials without paying for it all with -- if he had to pay -- to pay a such a reduced price as he can get the subcontractors to take because of threats to take them off to other places and so forth.","start":3120.052,"stop":3144.062,"duration":24.01},{"text":"And that he can see -- this whole contract, 13 pages of fine print, hadn't got but one single thing in it that the main contractor promises to do, every other paragraph as an agreement that the subcontractor shall not, but his one obligation was to pay and to pay promptly under that provision.","start":3144.062,"stop":3162.972,"duration":18.91},{"text":"And we say he conceived this scheme to avoid that payment and that one means by which he intended to avoid it was by use, by insertion of and use of this arbitration provision that when a claim arose and the man says, “I'm entitled of $90,000 you haven't paid”, that he would say, “Well, I'm not going to pay you.","start":3162.972,"stop":3182.122,"duration":19.15},{"text":"I'm going to take you to New York and we'll go arbitrate it up there” and we specifically allege in our complaint that our man would not be able to take the witnesses to New York.","start":3182.122,"stop":3191.113,"duration":8.99}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":3191.113,"stop":3200.874,"duration":9.76}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3200.874,"stop":3201.551,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":3201.551,"stop":3213.903,"duration":12.35}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Same side, Your Honor.","start":3213.903,"stop":3214.877,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] part of your argument is that the alleged fraud leads to the conclusion that [Inaudible] arbitration section of the contract is unfair to them because it results in the fact that you had [Inaudible] as you said they have to go to New York.","start":3214.877,"stop":3250.229,"duration":35.35}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, Your Honor --","start":3250.229,"stop":3251.152,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"On a second thought, would that still hold --","start":3251.152,"stop":3254.683,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Our allegation is that they put in there intending to use it knowing that we would not be able to properly present the claim in New York and that by using the arbitration proceeding, they would cut down what we were entitled to.","start":3254.683,"stop":3266.067,"duration":11.38}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well assume that the law is despite what this contract said, the contract must be read in light of the provision in several arbitration acts [Inaudible] assuming that the law is under those circumstances that the general contractor is seeking to deal -- to enforce the arbitration provision.","start":3266.067,"stop":3285.836,"duration":19.77},{"text":"Now, if Section 4 applies that the arbitration [Inaudible] take place in Georgia, then of course, how would you feel about that?","start":3285.836,"stop":3297.938,"duration":12.1}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that in an arbitration, as I argued yesterday, that we would not be able to properly present this fraud issue because it's a complicated question of law that ought to be presided over by a judge and the jury of fact-finding issue should -- finding the issues of fact should be instructed by one learned in the law as to what law is on this issue.","start":3297.938,"stop":3316.599,"duration":18.66},{"text":"And that the arbitrators --","start":3316.599,"stop":3317.544,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] to lawfully discharge that Section would apply?","start":3317.544,"stop":3332.148,"duration":14.6}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the la -- in labor issue is a place where arbitration works fine because generally, it's a fact issue, as Your Honor pose it, as to whether he was improperly discharged as the facts of the things, but -- I think there is such a clear overriding public policy in the Miller Act that a person shall had the right to sue and Congress didn't stop there by saying he had the right to sue.","start":3332.148,"stop":3354.736,"duration":22.59},{"text":"They, I say, had in mind the provisions it would have authorized the stay if they had not going on and say it and shall have the right to prosecute said action to final execution and judgment and the right to prosecute means to carry on and then never stop until you get a final judgment and I say Congress had in mind that such a suit for the relief of people who furnished improvements for the public works, furnished labor or materials that that suit is here to stop, that they ought to have a ready remedy and access to the Courts to enforce it.","start":3354.736,"stop":3388.68,"duration":33.94}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose that this contract provision is read [Inaudible].","start":3388.68,"stop":3394.299,"duration":5.62},{"text":"That I have read all the rest of the contract and notwithstanding, I go about the remedy [Inaudible]","start":3394.299,"stop":3411.499,"duration":17.2}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"After the controversy had arisen?","start":3411.499,"stop":3413.189,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":3413.189,"stop":3413.82,"duration":0.63},{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":3413.82,"stop":3416.614,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it's something he couldn't waive, that's my position.","start":3416.614,"stop":3419.323,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":3419.323,"stop":3420.128,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"It's my position he could not have waived it in advance.","start":3420.128,"stop":3422.416,"duration":2.29}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Could not have.","start":3422.416,"stop":3423.152,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3423.152,"stop":3423.902,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Can you distinguish between an agreement and such outside of the general contract [Inaudible].","start":3423.902,"stop":3435.759,"duration":11.86}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"I think there is a very definite distinction in the law applicable as to whether you can waive something in advance or where after your rights has arisen, you can agree to waive certain rights.","start":3435.759,"stop":3444.925,"duration":9.17},{"text":"There's definitely policy of law as I understand against waiving rights granted to you, where the man blanks, signed a blank check, giving them away as what this amounts to, but after you have a full realization of what it is you've given up, it is easier for the Court to say that you ought to be bound by an agreement to give it up.","start":3444.925,"stop":3460.312,"duration":15.39}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You are saying that what's been held many times, I think, is a different between a general contract made long before any controversy arises to waive your right to go into Court, and an agreement after dispute is arisen, and that the dispute as to how much is owed -- or whether they could go in, you're saying there's a difference between those and you are saying that under the Miller Act, they're entitled to have that trial although you wouldn't say I assume that if it had a controversy and been argued over and they then agree to submit it to arbitration that particular thing couldn't be arbitrated.","start":3460.312,"stop":3501.274,"duration":40.96}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- (Voice Overlap) I wouldn't concede that it would be enforceable if it were signed after the dispute arose, because in the Brooklyn Savings Bank versus O'Neil case where there was no specific prohibition.","start":3501.274,"stop":3514.161,"duration":12.89},{"text":"That's one thing I want to point out, unless it had to be an argued that in that case, there was a provision against waiver, there was not.","start":3514.161,"stop":3520.205,"duration":6.04},{"text":"That's the very thing the Court decided that even the absence of a prohibition against waiver, there can be no waiver of rights granted by an Act where waive them would (Voice Overlap).","start":3520.205,"stop":3529.578,"duration":9.37}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You're going there out on the basis that the Act prevents it at all?","start":3529.578,"stop":3534.002,"duration":4.42}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3534.002,"stop":3534.229,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Before or afterwards?","start":3534.229,"stop":3535.61,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir and in that case, the rights had arisen, this is what I'm getting at.","start":3535.61,"stop":3539.396,"duration":3.79},{"text":"At the time the waiver was signed, the rights had already arisen.","start":3539.396,"stop":3543.511,"duration":4.11},{"text":"And there was in the Act nothing prohibiting a waiver and yet this Court said that the congressional purpose is so clear that there shall not be a waiver.","start":3543.511,"stop":3551.945,"duration":8.43},{"text":"We won't permit it even though the waiver was signed after the rights have all approved.","start":3551.945,"stop":3555.91,"duration":3.96}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"We had that same question of very much the same of FELA case in Duncan against Thompson where the Act was construed as not allowing the man to sign the paper that would give up his rights even after the accident had occurred.","start":3555.91,"stop":3574.037,"duration":18.13}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't your basic position that the Arbitration Act doesn't apply to Miller Act cases?","start":3574.037,"stop":3579.361,"duration":5.32}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"That is not true.","start":3579.361,"stop":3579.676,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"That's your basic position.","start":3579.676,"stop":3580.945,"duration":1.27},{"text":"All these arguments you are making really comes down to that.","start":3580.945,"stop":3583.15,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"It comes down to that Your Honor, that the Miller Act has such a clear policy to prosecute the action to final execution.","start":3583.15,"stop":3588.782,"duration":5.63}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"And if you're wrong in that, what's left of your argument?","start":3588.782,"stop":3594.414,"duration":5.63}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if I'm wrong in that, the only other position I have is that we are not engaged in commerce within the meaning of the Arbitration Act.","start":3594.414,"stop":3604.746,"duration":10.33},{"text":"Now Mr. --","start":3604.746,"stop":3605.849,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] suppose Miller Act that nevertheless must take place in Georgia?","start":3605.849,"stop":3612.808,"duration":6.96}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I certainly take that position.","start":3612.808,"stop":3615.415,"duration":2.61},{"text":"I asked Mr. Justice Black yesterday that I didn't waive that claim.","start":3615.415,"stop":3619.342,"duration":3.93},{"text":"It should be --","start":3619.342,"stop":3619.609,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You have also insisted that you have alleged fraud.","start":3619.609,"stop":3622.664,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes and (Voice Overlap) contract.","start":3622.664,"stop":3625.514,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And that they have refused to let you offer evidence to show they were guilty of fraud.","start":3625.514,"stop":3630.663,"duration":5.15}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"That is my position.","start":3630.663,"stop":3631.366,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"There's no allegation in your complaint, is there, that the Arbitration Clause distinguished from the whole contract was induced by fraud.","start":3631.366,"stop":3640.676,"duration":9.31}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"We allege in the complaint that the Arbitration Clause was inserted in the contract --","start":3640.676,"stop":3645.169,"duration":4.49}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"Was a part --","start":3645.169,"stop":3645.529,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"And part of the one illegal spilling.","start":3645.529,"stop":3647.041,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"Part of the overriding fraud.","start":3647.041,"stop":3649.948,"duration":2.91}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3649.948,"stop":3650.815,"duration":0.87},{"text":"Now, with these details, subparagraph just set out the manner in which they carried into effect the one scheme they had which was to obtain money and materials without paying both as they're required to do.","start":3650.815,"stop":3662.619,"duration":11.8}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":3662.619,"stop":3674.413,"duration":11.79}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, I'd say there's a definite distinction in the facts there and I was about to try to point out that Mr. Edenfield said yesterday this was additions to the existing AFA's -- the record shows clearly on page 73, 74, 77 and 97 that this was pure woods ground.","start":3674.413,"stop":3693.199,"duration":18.79},{"text":"Nothing there before based on in this construction and that the nearest airbase was 15 miles away and the intervening property was private property, had no connection with, it has no facility to perform at this airbase.","start":3693.199,"stop":3705.216,"duration":12.02},{"text":"It's operated by the army while the Warner Robins Air Base as operated by the Air Force.","start":3705.216,"stop":3711.409,"duration":6.19},{"text":"It's not a part of an existing thing.","start":3711.409,"stop":3712.962,"duration":1.55},{"text":"It's brand new construction and under that theory, it's not something added too and it was different in the case Your Honor brought.","start":3712.962,"stop":3718.902,"duration":5.94},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3718.902,"stop":3719.436,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not only to say your [Inaudible] not to be applied in this case but that an arbitration provision in the contract is not enforceable in Miller Act case.","start":3719.436,"stop":3733.735,"duration":14.3}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"In the Miller Act case --","start":3733.735,"stop":3734.896,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's a considerably different proposition.","start":3734.896,"stop":3739.368,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it's two-pronged proposition and that I should have point out that this proceeding they brought in New York was not just notice of arbitration.","start":3739.368,"stop":3747.739,"duration":8.37},{"text":"It's a suit to compel arbitration and the statute disclosed in the record in New York as almost word per word Section 4 of the United States Arbitration Act.","start":3747.739,"stop":3757.144,"duration":9.4},{"text":"They have the joint --","start":3757.144,"stop":3757.926,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What you're saying is that an agreement to arbitrate in government construction situation is not enforceable even in the absence of any agreements to arbitrate outside the district in the absence of fraud or anything else.","start":3757.926,"stop":3775.428,"duration":17.5},{"text":"That your position is simply is that the contract to arbitrate is not enforceable in Miller Act cases.","start":3775.428,"stop":3782.124,"duration":6.7}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"I do definitely take that position, Your Honor.","start":3782.124,"stop":3783.791,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"In Miller Act cases.","start":3783.791,"stop":3785.194,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"George C. Grant","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's what -- well I assume Mr. Justice White had reference to Miller Act cases that they just can't, you can't prosecute it and hold it stay and go arbitrate and comply with the terms of Miller Act in our position.","start":3785.194,"stop":3797.718,"duration":12.52},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3797.718,"stop":3800.626,"duration":2.91}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Apr  16 - 17, 1963","petitioner":"Moseley","respondent":"Electronic & Missile Facilities, Inc.","docket":"401","citation":"374 US 167 (1963)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/374/167","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 17, 1963"}